)@@G@@@F@@@@USERS.  THINGS WILL BE KEPT IN THIS DOCUMENT FOR A MONTH OR TWO.  TG
)@@G@@@G@@@@THE BASIC PURPOSE IS TO MAKE IT UNNECESSARY TO GET A LOT OF LISTINTH
)@@G@@GS    @G@@@@OF THE BASIC 1108 DOCUMENT, SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL-D, WHICH HAS GTI
)@@G@@ROWN TO     @F@@@@A FAIRLY SIZABLE TEXT.  YOU MIGHT TRY GETTING A COPY OTJ
)@@G@@F THIS NEWS @G@@@@DOCUMENT EVERY FEW WEEKS TO SEE IF ANYTHING OF INTERESTK
)@@G@@T HAS HAPPENED.   @G@@@@IT MIGHT ALSO BE A GOOD IDEA IF YOU HELP SPREAD TL
)@@G@@THE WORD ABOUT THIS     @G@@@@DOCUMENT'S EXISTENCE, SINCE IT IS NEW AND TM
)@@G@@MANY USERS PROBABLY HAVEN'T   @#@@@@YET HEARD OF IT.  @@@@@@@G@@@@THE DOTN
)@@G@@CUMENTS CURRENTLY OF INTEREST TO SNOBOL4 USERS CAN BE PRINTED     @B@@@@TO
)@@G@@BY USING THE FOLLOWING CONTROL CARDS:     @D@@@@   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.NEWSTP
)@@G@@           (THIS DOCUMENT)    @F@@@@   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL-D       (TQ
)@@G@@SUPPLEMENT TO SNOBOL MANUAL)  @F@@@@   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.DOCUMENT       (TR
)@@G@@DESCRIBES SNOBOL LIBRARY)     @F@@@@   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.EXTERNAL-D     (TS
)@@G@@EXTERNAL FORTRAN FUNCTIONS)   @@@@@@@G@@@@******************************TT
)@@G@@******************************************@F@@@@IT IS NOW POSSIBLE TO USTU
)@@G@@E FUNCTIONS WRITTEN IN FORTRAN OR 1108    @F@@@@ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE WITH ATV
)@@G@@ SNOBOL PROGRAM.  THIS 'EXTERNAL FUNCTION'@E@@@@FACILITY IS DESCRIBED INTW
)@@G@@ A DOCUMENT THAT CAN BE PRINTED BY: @ @@@@   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.EXTERNAL-DTX
)@@G@@@@@@@@@G@@@@************************************************************TY
)@@G@@************___@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@TZ
)@@G@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@*[@@@@*SDFF*@]@@@@1 MARCH 1971@G@@@@************UA
)@@G@@************************************************************@G@@@@******UB
)@@G@@******************************************************************@F@@@@UC
)@@G@@THIS DOCUMENT DESCRIBES THE USE OF FORTRAN OR ASSEMBLY-LANGUAGE   @G@@@@UD
)@@G@@FUNCTIONS WITH SNOBOL4 PROGRAMS ON THE 1108.  SUCH 'EXTERNAL' FUNCTIONS UE
)@@G@@@G@@@@ARE INCLUDED IN A SNOBOL PROGRAM BY 'COLLECTING' THE FUNCTIONS WITUF
)@@G@@H     @G@@@@A SPECIAL 'RELOCATABLE' VERSION OF SNOBOL AND A TABLE DESCRIUG
)@@G@@BING THE    @F@@@@FUNCTIONS.  THIS PRODUCES A VERSION OF THE SNOBOL4 SYSUH
)@@G@@TEM THAT    @F@@@@CONTAINS YOUR FUNCTIONS, AND IT CAN BE USED TO EXECUTEUI
)@@G@@ SNOBOL4    @F@@@@PROGRAMS THAT CAN THEN USE ANY OF THESE EXTRA FUNCTIONUJ
)@@G@@S.  A FULLY @F@@@@DYNAMIC FACILITY ISN'T POSSIBLE BECAUSE OF RESTRICTIONUK
)@@G@@S IMPOSED BY@G@@@@THE 1108'S ORGANIZATION, BUT IT IS POSSIBLE TO USE A PUL
)@@G@@RE-DETERMINED     @ @@@@SET OF EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS.    @@@@@@@F@@@@BEFOREUM
)@@G@@ THE MEANS OF DOING THIS IS DESCRIBED, A FEW WARNINGS ARE   @G@@@@IN ORDUN
)@@G@@ER.  FIRST, THE SNOBOL-FORTRAN INTERFACE SHOULD BE CONSIDERED     @G@@@@UO
)@@G@@TO BE 'EXPERIMENTAL' FOR SEVERAL MONTHS, AND ITS SPECIFICATIONS ARE     UP
)@@G@@@G@@@@QUITE LIKELY TO UNDERGO SOME CHANGES AT FIRST.  WE WILL TRY TO STIUQ
)@@G@@CK    @F@@@@TO EXTENSIONS OF THE BASIC FACILITY DESCRIBED HERE, BUT IT MUR
)@@G@@AY BE @G@@@@NECESSARY TO MAKE A FEW CHANGES THAT MIGHT AFFECT EXISTING PUS
)@@G@@ROGRAMS.    @G@@@@ALSO, THERE ARE PROBABLY A LOT OF BUGS THAT AREN'T KNOUT
)@@G@@WN YET IN THE     @G@@@@INTERFACING ROUTINES.  WITH COOPERATION FROM USEUU
)@@G@@RS, MOST OF THEM WILL   @^@@@@BE QUICKLY ELIMINATED.  @@@@@@@G@@@@A SERIUV
)@@G@@OUS PROBLEM WITH THIS INTERFACE TO WHICH THERE IS NO SOLUTION     @F@@@@UW
)@@G@@IS THAT FORTRAN PROVIDES NO BOUNDS CHECKING FOR ITS ARRAYS.  THIS @G@@@@UX
)@@G@@MEANS THAT A FORTRAN FUNCTION CAN ACTUALLY ACCESS MEMORY OUTSIDE OF     UY
)@@G@@@G@@@@THE AREA ALLOCATED TO IT, AND THIS COULD EASILY DESTROY INFORMATIOUZ
)@@G@@N     @F@@@@VITAL TO THE SNOBOL4 SYSTEM.  THIS WILL USUALLY SHOW UP SOMEVA
)@@G@@TIME  @F@@@@AFTER THE FUNCTION RETURNS TO THE SNOBOL PROGRAM, AS EITHER VB
)@@G@@VERY  @G@@@@STRANGE BEHAVIOR OR SUDDEN DEATH OF THE PROGRAM (OR BOTH).  VC
)@@G@@YOU MUST    @G@@@@BE VERY CAREFUL TO ENSURE THAT EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS DON'VD
)@@G@@T WRITE OUTSIDE   @^@@@@THEIR PART OF MEMORY.   @@@@@@@G@@@@THIS ISN'T MVE
)@@G@@EANT TO SCARE PEOPLE AWAY FROM EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS.  ON THE  @F@@@@CONTRAVF
)@@G@@RY, WE WOULD LIKE TO ENCOURAGE PEOPLE TO MAKE AS MUCH USE OF@F@@@@THEM AVG
)@@G@@S THEY CAN, BECAUSE THIS IS THE ONLY WAY TO MAKE SURE THAT  @F@@@@EVERYTVH
)@@G@@HING WORKS PROPERLY.  ANYONE WHO USES EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS IS @G@@@@REQUESVI
)@@G@@TED TO SEND A NOTE TO JOHN CHAMBERS (C/O THE UWCC) DESCRIBING     @F@@@@VJ
)@@G@@WHAT HE HAS DONE AND ANY PROBLEMS ENCOUNTERED THAT PERTAIN TO THE @G@@@@VK
)@@G@@SNOBOL-FORTRAN INTERFACE.  IF YOU FIND ANY BUGS, THEY CAN BE CORRECTED  VL
)@@G@@@F@@@@FASTEST IF YOU CAN PROVIDE AS MUCH INFORMATION AS POSSIBLE ABOUT  VM
)@@G@@@G@@@@EXACTLY WHAT DOESN'T WORK.  THIS MEANS THAT SAYING 'MY PROGRAM DOEVN
)@@G@@SN'T  @F@@@@DO WHAT I THINK IT SHOULD' ISN'T NEARLY ENOUGH--IT IS NECESSVO
)@@G@@ARY TO@F@@@@FIND OUT JUST WHAT OPERATION DIDN'T WORK, WHAT ITS ARGUMENTSVP
)@@G@@ WERE,@G@@@@AND WHAT IT ACTUALLY DID.  INFORMATION ON THINGS THAT WORK CVQ
)@@G@@ORRECTLY    @F@@@@IS ALSO USEFUL--THERE ARE A LOT OF THINGS AROUND THAT VR
)@@G@@AREN'T KNOWN@G@@@@TO WORK PROPERLY BECAUSE NO INFORMATION HAS BEEN RECEIVS
)@@G@@VED FROM USERS    @F@@@@ABOUT THEM, AND THIS COULD MEAN EITHER THAT THEYVT
)@@G@@ WORK CORRECTLY OR@A@@@@THAT NOBODY HAS TRIED TO USE THEM.  @@@@@@@G@@@@VU
)@@G@@FURTHER EXTENSIONS OF THIS INTERFACE ARE PLANNED (PASSING ARRAYS AS     VV
)@@G@@@G@@@@PARAMETERS IS THE FIRST OF THEM).  IF YOU HAVE ANY MORE SUGGESTIONVW
)@@G@@S,    @F@@@@PLEASE TELL US ABOUT THEM (EXCEPT FOR SAYING WHERE WE CAN GOVX
)@@G@@ WITH @A@@@@IT ALL--WE ALREADY KNOW THAT!).     @@@@@@@F@@@@THIS INTERFAVY
)@@G@@CE IS STRICTLY AN 1108 FEATURE, AND ANY PROGRAM THAT  @F@@@@USES IT WILLVZ
)@@G@@ NOT RUN ON ANOTHER COMPUTER WITHOUT SOME EXTENSIVE   @F@@@@CHANGES.  ITWA
)@@G@@ HAS BEEN MODELLED ON THE INTERFACE SET UP FOR THE CDC@F@@@@6000-SERIES WB
)@@G@@BY MICHAEL SHAPIRO AT PURDUE, SO IT WON'T BE TOO HARD @G@@@@TO MOVE SUCHWC
)@@G@@ PROGRAMS TO ANY MACHINE IN THIS SERIES IF THIS VERSION     @F@@@@OF SNOWD
)@@G@@BOL4 IS AVAILABLE.  (MANY 6000-SERIES INSTALLATIONS HAVE IT.@G@@@@IF THEWE
)@@G@@ ONE YOU WANT TO USE DOESN'T, WE CAN TELL YOU HOW TO GET IT).     @G@@@@WF
)@@G@@THE IBM 360 HAS A SNOBOL-FORTRAN INTERFACE FOR OS WHICH IS A LITTLE     WG
)@@G@@@F@@@@LESS SIMILAR, BUT IT SHOULD STILL BE POSSIBLE TO TRANSFER PROGRAMSWH
)@@G@@@F@@@@TO ANY MACHINE USING OS WITHOUT ENCOUNTERING ANY INSURMOUNTABLE   WI
)@@G@@@F@@@@PROBLEMS.  IF YOU ARE CONSIDERING THE POSSIBILITY OF HAVING YOUR  WJ
)@@G@@@F@@@@PROGRAMS RUN ON ANY OF THESE MACHINES (WHO ISN'T?), AND YOU STICK WK
)@@G@@@G@@@@TO ASA FORTRAN-IV (PLUS THE EXTRA RETURN FUNCTIONS) YOU SHOULD HAVWL
)@@G@@E     @G@@@@RELATIVELY FEW PROBLEMS WITH INCOMPATIBILITY OF EITHER THE RWM
)@@G@@OUTINES     @G@@@@OR THE ABILITY TO CALL THEM FROM SNOBOL PROGRAMS ON ANWN
)@@G@@Y OF THESE THREE  @]@@@@COMPUTERS.  @@@@@@@G@@@@************************WO
)@@G@@************************************************@ @@@@SETTING UP EXTERNAWP
)@@G@@L FUNCTIONS.@@@@@@@F@@@@TO USE EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS IN SNOBOL4, FOUR STEPSWQ
)@@G@@ ARE NECESSARY:   @F@@@@   1) CREATE RELOCATABLE ELEMENTS FOR THEM, USINWR
)@@G@@G @FOR OR @ASM.   @F@@@@   2) CREATE A TABLE CALLED 'EXTERNAL' DESCRIBINWS
)@@G@@G THEM TO SNOBOL. @F@@@@   3) DO A @MAP TO BUILD A SNOBOL SYSTEM WITH YOWT
)@@G@@UR FUNCTIONS.     @G@@@@   4) CALL LOAD() WITHIN THE SNOBOL PROGRAM TO DWU
)@@G@@EFINE THE FUNCTIONS.    @G@@@@THE FIRST OF THESE IS THE SAME AS FOR ALL WV
)@@G@@FORTRAN OR ASSEMBLY-LANGUAGE  @F@@@@ROUTINES, AND IS DESCRIBED IN THEIR WW
)@@G@@RESPECTIVE MANUALS.  ANY ENTRY@G@@@@POINT IS ACCESSIBLE TO SNOBOL; IF ANWX
)@@G@@ ELEMENT CONTAINS SEVERAL ENTRY     @E@@@@POINTS, EACH ONE WILL BE TREATWY
)@@G@@ED AS A SEPARATE FUNCTION.    @@@@@@@G@@@@THE SECOND STEP IS TO USE THE WZ
)@@G@@ASSEMBLER TO CREATE A TABLE DESCRIBING    @C@@@@THE FUNCTIONS TO SNOBOL XA
)@@G@@IN THE FOLLOWING WAY:   @^@@@@   @ASM,IS  <TNAME>     @#@@@@   EXTERNAL*XB
)@@G@@.     @D@@@@         +  <NAME1>.               FIRST FUNCTION.    @ @@@@XC
)@@G@@         +  <P1>,<ENTRY1>.    @D@@@@         +  <NAME2>.               SXD
)@@G@@ECOND FUNCTION.   @ @@@@         +  <P2>,<ENTRY2>.    @]@@@@         .  XE
)@@G@@@]@@@@         :  @D@@@@         +  <NAMEN>.               N-TH FUNCTIONXF
)@@G@@.     @ @@@@         +  <PN>,ENTRYN>.     @E@@@@         +  0.          XG
)@@G@@           END-OF-TABLE MARKER.     @#@@@@         END.     @F@@@@THE TAXH
)@@G@@BLE CONTAINS ONE 2-WORD ENTRY FOR EACH FUNCTION.  THE FIRST @G@@@@WORD IXI
)@@G@@N EACH ENTRY IS A 6-CHARACTER STRING GIVING THE NAME THE SNOBOL   @G@@@@XJ
)@@G@@PROGRAM IS TO USE FOR THE FUNCTION.  IT IS LEFT-JUSTIFIED AND FILLED    XK
)@@G@@@F@@@@WITH BLANKS.  NOTE THAT THE PROGRAM CAN USE A NAME OF MORE THAN 6 XL
)@@G@@@G@@@@CHARACTERS, BUT ONLY THE FIRST 6 ARE SIGNIFICANT AS FAR AS THE ROUXM
)@@G@@TINES @B@@@@THAT HANDLE THE INTERFACE ARE CONCERNED.  @@@@@@@F@@@@THE SEXN
)@@G@@COND WORD OF A TABLE ENTRY CONTAINS TWO HALF-WORDS ITEMS:   @D@@@@   <PIXO
)@@G@@>  IS THE NUMBER OF PARAMETERS FOR THE FUNCTION.@A@@@@   <ENTRYI> IS THEXP
)@@G@@ ENTRY POINT.     @F@@@@NOTE THAT THE NAME OF THE ENTRY POINT DOESN'T HAXQ
)@@G@@VE TO RESEMBLE THE@F@@@@NAME USED WITHIN THE SNOBOL PROGRAM, THOUGH THEYXR
)@@G@@ ARE USUALLY VERY @C@@@@SIMILAR TO AVOID CONFUSION.  FOR AN EXAMPLE:    XS
)@@G@@@^@@@@   @ASM,IS  TPF$.FCTS   @#@@@@   EXTERNAL*.     @^@@@@         +  XT
)@@G@@'SIN   '.   @#@@@@         +  1,SIN.@^@@@@         +  'INITDI'.   @ @@@@XU
)@@G@@         +  4,INITDISPLAY.    @^@@@@         +  'BLORKL'.   @^@@@@      XV
)@@G@@   +  2,MEEBX.    @E@@@@         +  0.          REMEMBER THE END-OF-TABLXW
)@@G@@E MARKER!   @#@@@@         END.     @F@@@@THIS DEFINES 3 FUNCTIONS CALLEXX
)@@G@@D 'SIN', 'INITDI', AND 'BLORKL' (THE@F@@@@LAST TWO MAY HAVE LONGER NAMESXY
)@@G@@ IN THE SNOBOL PROGRAM); THEIR ENTRY@G@@@@POINTS ARE CALLED 'SIN', 'INITXZ
)@@G@@DISPLAY', AND 'MEEBX' AND THEY HAVE 1,    @G@@@@4, AND 2 PARAMETERS RESPYA
)@@G@@ECTIVELY.  NOTE THAT THE THIRD ONE VIOLATES     @G@@@@THE ADVICE TO MAKEYB
)@@G@@ THE 'INTERNAL' NAME SIMILAR TO THE 'EXTERNAL' NAME.  @@@@@@@G@@@@AFTER YC
)@@G@@THE FUNCTIONS ALL HAVE BEEN COMPILED OR ASSEMBLED AND THE TABLE   @G@@@@YD
)@@G@@CALLED 'EXTERNAL' HAS BEEN DEFINED, THE THIRD STEP IS TO DO A 'COLLEC-  YE
)@@G@@@G@@@@TION' TO BUILD YOUR OWN PERSONAL COPY OF THE SNOBOL SYSTEM, AUGMENYF
)@@G@@TED   @D@@@@BY YOUR FUNCTIONS.  THIS IS DONE IN THE FOLLOWING WAY:@^@@@@YG
)@@G@@   @MAP,I   ,<SNAME>    @]@@@@   IN <ELT1>@]@@@@   IN <ELT2>@[@@@@   .  YH
)@@G@@@[@@@@   :  @]@@@@   IN <ELTN>@#@@@@   IN <TNAME>     @^@@@@   IN SNOBOLYI
)@@G@@*LIB.SNOBOL @F@@@@WHERE <ELT1>, <ELT2>,..., <ELTN> ARE THE NAMES OF THE YJ
)@@G@@RELOCATABLE @F@@@@ELEMENTS THAT CONTAIN YOUR FUNCTIONS, AND <TNAME> IS TYK
)@@G@@HE ELEMENT  @F@@@@THAT CONTAINS THE TABLE 'EXTERNAL'.  THE 'IN' CARD THAYL
)@@G@@T REFERENCES@G@@@@SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL MUST BE THE LAST CARD.  (WHY WON'T BYM
)@@G@@E EXPLAINED HERE.)@G@@@@TO CONTINUE THE ABOVE EXAMPLE, SUPPOSE THAT THE YN
)@@G@@ENTRY 'SIN' IS IN THE   @G@@@@ELEMENT TPF$.SIN, AND 'INITDISPLAY' AND 'MYO
)@@G@@EEBX' ARE ALTERNATE ENTRIES   @D@@@@IN SMITH.IOPACKAGE.  THE COLLECTION YP
)@@G@@WOULD LOOK LIKE:  @^@@@@   @MAP,I   ,.SNOBOL    @#@@@@   IN TPF$.SIN    YQ
)@@G@@@^@@@@   IN SMITH.IOPACKAGE   @#@@@@   IN TPF$.FCTS   @^@@@@   IN SNOBOLYR
)@@G@@*LIB.SNOBOL @F@@@@THIS WILL CREATE AN ELEMENT .SNOBOL (OR TPF$.SNOBOL, TYS
)@@G@@O BE MORE   @F@@@@PRECISE) WHICH CONTAINS THE SNOBOL SYSTEM AND THE THREYT
)@@G@@E DESIRED   @F@@@@FUNCTIONS.  WE CAN USE THIS VERSION OF SNOBOL TO EXECUYU
)@@G@@TE A PROGRAM@A@@@@BY USING THE FOLLOWING CONTROL CARD:@]@@@@   @<SNAME> YV
)@@G@@@A@@@@WHICH IN THE ABOVE EXAMPLE WOULD BE:@]@@@@   @.SNOBOL @C@@@@AND FOYW
)@@G@@LLOWING THIS WITH THE SNOBOL PROGRAM.     @@@@@@@G@@@@WITHIN THE SNOBOL YX
)@@G@@PROGRAM IT IS NECESSARY TO DEFINE EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS  @F@@@@BY CALLS OF YY
)@@G@@LOAD(S), WHERE THE STRING S DESCRIBES THE FUNCTION AND@B@@@@THE TYPES OFYZ
)@@G@@ ITS ARGUMENTS AS FOLLOWS:    @C@@@@   <NAME> ( <TYPE1> , ... , <TYPEN> ZA
)@@G@@) <TYPE>    @F@@@@WHERE <NAME> IS THE FUNCTION'S NAME, <TYPE1>, ..., <TYZB
)@@G@@PEN> ARE THE@G@@@@TYPES REQUIRED FOR ITS ARGUMENTS, AND <TYPE> IS THE EXZC
)@@G@@PECTED TYPE OF    @F@@@@THE FUNCTION'S RETURN VALUE.  THE NAME MUST AGREZD
)@@G@@E IN ITS FIRST 6  @G@@@@CHARACTERS WITH SOME NAME IN THE TABLE 'EXTERNALZE
)@@G@@', AND THE NUMBER OF    @G@@@@PARAMETERS MUST AGREE WITH THE NUMBER SPECZF
)@@G@@IFIED BY THE TABLE ENTRY,     @F@@@@OR LOAD() WILL FAIL.  ALSO, THERE ARZG
)@@G@@E ONLY A FEW TYPES THAT CAN BE@G@@@@PASSED TO AN EXTERNAL FUNCTION--CURRZH
)@@G@@ENTLY ONLY INTEGERS, REALS, AND     @G@@@@STRINGS WILL BE ACCEPTED, AND ZI
)@@G@@THE RETURN CAN BE ONLY OF TYPE INTEGER OR @F@@@@REAL.  (IT WILL BE SHOWNZJ
)@@G@@ LATER HOW A STRING CAN BE RETURNED.)     @@@@@@@F@@@@TO CONTINUE THE ABZK
)@@G@@OVE EXAMPLE, WE MIGHT DEFINE OUR THREE EXTERNAL @A@@@@FUNCTIONS IN THE FZL
)@@G@@OLLOWING WAYS:    @^@@@@   LOAD('SIN(REAL)REAL')@E@@@@   LOAD('INITDISPLZM
)@@G@@AY(INTEGER,INTEGER,REAL,STRING)INTEGER')  @B@@@@   LOAD('BLORKLE(STRING,ZN
)@@G@@INTEGER)INTEGER') @G@@@@************************************************ZO
)@@G@@************************@@@@@@@ @@@@USE OF EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS.    @@@@@@ZP
)@@G@@@G@@@@AN EXTERNAL FUNCTION IS CALLED IN THE SAME MANNER AS ANY OTHER SNOZQ
)@@G@@BOL   @G@@@@FUNCTION.  THERE IS CURRENTLY THE RESTRICTION THAT YOU MUST ZR
)@@G@@PROVIDE     @G@@@@THE 'CORRECT' NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS, OR ERROR 25 (INCORRZS
)@@G@@ECT NUMBER OF     @G@@@@ARGUMENTS) WILL OCCUR.  IF ANY ARGUMENT IS OF THZT
)@@G@@E WRONG TYPE, IT WILL   @G@@@@BE CONVERTED IF POSSIBLE, AND IF THIS CAN'ZU
)@@G@@T BE DONE, ERROR 1 (ILLEGAL   @G@@@@DATA TYPE) WILL OCCUR.  IF THERE AREZV
)@@G@@ THE RIGHT NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS, AND @G@@@@THEY CAN ALL BE CONVERTED TO TZW
)@@G@@HE REQUIRED TYPE, A FORTRAN-LIKE CALLING  @G@@@@SEQUENCE WILL BE GENERATZX
)@@G@@ED AND A TRANSFER WILL BE MADE TO THE FUNCTION'S@G@@@@ENTRY POINT.  (FORZY
)@@G@@ ASSEMBLY-LANGUAGE PROGRAMMERS, THE FORTRAN CALLING   @ @@@@SEQUENCE IS ZZ
)@@G@@DESCRIBED BELOW.) @@@@@@@G@@@@YOU MAY HAVE WONDERED HOW STRINGS CAN BE PAA
)@@G@@ASSED TO A FORTRAN FUNCTION   @G@@@@WHEN FORTRAN HAS NO TYPE 'STRING'.  AB
)@@G@@A STRING REPRESENTATION HAS BEEN    @G@@@@DEFINED FOR FORTRAN THAT SHOULAC
)@@G@@D BE FAIRLY EASY TO USE.  A STRING WILL   @F@@@@BE PASSED TO A FORTRAN RAD
)@@G@@OUTINE AS A ONE-DIMENSIONAL INTEGER ARRAY,@F@@@@SAY IS(N), WHOSE FIRST IAE
)@@G@@TEM, IS(1), IS THE SIZE OF THE STRING IN  @G@@@@CHARACTERS.  THE REST OFAF
)@@G@@ THE ARRAY, IS(2), IS(3), ETC., CONTAINS THE    @G@@@@STRING IN THE FORMAG
)@@G@@AT HANDLED BY ENCODE AND DECODE--6 CHARACTERS PER     @F@@@@WORD ON THE AH
)@@G@@1108.  THIS SAME STRING REPRESENTATION IS ALSO USED TO@F@@@@RETURN STRINAI
)@@G@@GS TO SNOBOL; THIS WILL BE DESCRIBED SHORTLY.  NOTE   @G@@@@THAT THE ARRAJ
)@@G@@AY THAT CONTAINS A STRING WILL BE JUST BIG ENOUGH TO HOLD   @G@@@@THE STAK
)@@G@@RING.  THE FORTRAN FUNCTION CAN CHANGE THIS ARRAY IF YOU WANT IT  @G@@@@AL
)@@G@@TO, BUT YOU MUST NOT WRITE BEYOND ITS END, OR YOU WILL PROBABLY DESTROY AM
)@@G@@@G@@@@SOME INFORMATION THAT THE SNOBOL4 SPACE-ALLOCATION ROUTINES NEED, AN
)@@G@@AND   @F@@@@YOUR PROGRAM WILL DIE VERY SHORTLY AFTER THE FUNCTION RETURNAO
)@@G@@S.    @@@@@@@G@@@@A MINOR INCONVENIENCE IS THAT PARAMETERS OF TYPE STRINAP
)@@G@@G MUST BE SPEC-   @G@@@@IFIED IN A FORTRAN FUNCTION BY A DIMENSION STATEAQ
)@@G@@MENT.  THERE IS, OF     @G@@@@COURSE, NO WAY TO KNOW BEFOREHAND HOW BIG AR
)@@G@@THE ARRAY WILL BE, SO YOU     @G@@@@CAN USE ANY BOUND YOU LIKE.  YOU JUSAS
)@@G@@T NEED TO TELL THE FORTRAN COMPILER @G@@@@THAT THE PARAMETER IS A SINGLYAT
)@@G@@-SUBSCRIPTED INTEGER ARRAY.  SINCE FORTRAN@F@@@@DOESN'T OBJECT TO INDEXIAU
)@@G@@NG BEYOND THE UPPER BOUND OF AN ARRAY, THE@F@@@@BOUND YOU GIVE IS STRICTAV
)@@G@@LY A 'DUMMY' BOUND REQUIRED BY FORTRAN BUT@G@@@@OTHERWISE MEANINGLESS.  AW
)@@G@@FOR EXAMPLE, IF F() IS AN EXTERNAL FUNCTION     @G@@@@DEFINED BY LOAD('FAX
)@@G@@(INTEGER,STRING)REAL'), THE FUNCTION SHOULD START     @^@@@@WITH SOMETHIAY
)@@G@@NG LIKE:    @ @@@@         FUNCTION F(I,IST)    @ @@@@         DIMENSIONAZ
)@@G@@ IST(15)    @F@@@@THE DIMENSION STATEMENT SIMPLY TELLS FORTRAN TO TREAT BA
)@@G@@IST LIKE A  @G@@@@ONE-DIMENSIONAL INTEGER ARRAY, AND THE NUMBER 15 COULDBB
)@@G@@ BE ANY OTHER     @^@@@@(POSITIVE) INTEGER.     @@@@@@@F@@@@TO RETURN A BC
)@@G@@VALUE, A NORMAL FORTRAN RETURN CAN BE USED, AND SNOBOL@G@@@@WILL ASSUME BD
)@@G@@THAT THE TYPE IS THE ONE INDICATED IN THE CALL OF LOAD()    @G@@@@THAT DBE
)@@G@@EFINED THE FUNCTION.  ONLY INTEGERS AND REALS CAN BE RETURNED     @]@@@@BF
)@@G@@IN THIS WAY.@@@@@@@F@@@@IN ADDITION TO THE NORMAL FORTRAN RETURN, SNOBOLBG
)@@G@@ CONTAINS A SET OF@G@@@@ENTRY POINTS THAT LOOK LIKE SUBROUTINES TO FORTRBH
)@@G@@AN WHICH CAN BE USED    @F@@@@TO 'GET AROUND' THE FORTRAN RETURN MECHANIBI
)@@G@@SM AND PRODUCE A MORE   @G@@@@SNOBOL-LIKE RETURN.  THEIR NAMES ALL STARTBJ
)@@G@@ WITH 'RTN' PLUS A CHARAC-    @G@@@@TER INDICATING THE TYPE OF RETURN.  BK
)@@G@@THE RETURN FUNCTIONS IMPLEMENTED    @]@@@@SO FAR ARE: @C@@@@   (FORTRAN BL
)@@G@@STATEMENT)             (RESULT)     @B@@@@   CALL RTNF                  BM
)@@G@@     FAILURE@E@@@@   CALL RTNI(I)                    RETURN THE INTEGER BN
)@@G@@I     @E@@@@   CALL RTNR(R)                    RETURN THE REAL NUMBER R BO
)@@G@@@G@@@@   CALL RTNS(S(1))                 RETURN THE STRING IN THE ARRAY BP
)@@G@@S     @@@@@@@G@@@@THESE CAUSE A RETURN WITHOUT REGARD FOR THE TYPE OF THBQ
)@@G@@E FUNCTION THEY   @G@@@@ARE USED IN.  THUS, IF THE ABOVE 'REAL' FUNCTIONBR
)@@G@@ F CALLS RTNI(I), I     @G@@@@WILL BE RETURNED AND THE CALLING SNOBOL STBS
)@@G@@ATEMENT WILL ACCEPT IT AS AN  @F@@@@INTEGER.  RTNS IS THE ONLY WAY TO REBT
)@@G@@TURN A STRING FROM AN EXTERNAL@F@@@@FUNCTION.  AS A SPECIAL CASE, RTNS(0BU
)@@G@@) WILL RETURN THE NULL STRING.@@@@@@@F@@@@A PECULIAR THING ABOUT THESE RBV
)@@G@@ETURN FUNCTIONS:  THEY ALL CAUSE AN @F@@@@IMMEDIATE RETURN TO SNOBOL EVEBW
)@@G@@N IF THE EXTERNAL FUNCTION IS WITHIN@F@@@@A SET OF NESTED CALLS.  THUS IBX
)@@G@@F A SNOBOL PROGRAM CALLS THE FORTRAN@G@@@@FUNCTION F, AND F CALLS ANOTHEBY
)@@G@@R FORTRAN FUNCTION G, IF G CALLS, SAY,    @F@@@@RTNS, THE RETURN WON'T BBZ
)@@G@@E TO F BUT ALL THE WAY BACK TO THE SNOBOL @G@@@@PROGRAM.  THIS HAPPENS BCA
)@@G@@ECAUSE SNOBOL KNOWS NOTHING ABOUT WHAT GOES     @F@@@@ON AFTER A FORTRANCB
)@@G@@ FUNCTION IS CALLED, AND IN PARTICULAR IT KNOWS @F@@@@NOTHING ABOUT ANY CC
)@@G@@FURTHER FUNCTION CALLS THAT MAY BE MADE.  WHEN A@G@@@@REQUEST TO RETURN CD
)@@G@@IS MADE BY CALLING ONE OF THE ABOVE FUNCTIONS, AS     @G@@@@PART OF SNOBCE
)@@G@@OL THEY ASSUME YOU MEAN TO RETURN FROM THE ONLY EXTERNAL    @E@@@@FUNCTICF
)@@G@@ON THEY KNOW WAS CALLED--THE ONE CALLED FROM SNOBOL.  @@@@@@@G@@@@ANOTHECG
)@@G@@R PROBLEM IS WITH ERROR TERMINATION INSIDE A FORTRAN ROUTINE.     @F@@@@CH
)@@G@@INCLUSION OF ANY FORTRAN FUNCTION CAUSES THE INCLUSION OF ALL OF  @F@@@@CI
)@@G@@FORTRAN'S ERROR RECOVERY ROUTINES, BUT THEY AREN'T ALL SET UP TO  @F@@@@CJ
)@@G@@WORK VERY WELL WHEN THEY RUN INTO SNOBOL.  FUNNY THINGS MAY HAPPEN@F@@@@CK
)@@G@@AS A RESULT.  FOR INSTANCE, WHEN A 'WALKBACK' STARTS, IT WILL BE  @F@@@@CL
)@@G@@CORRECT FOR THE FORTRAN ROUTINES IT HANDLES, BUT WHEN IT GETS BACK@F@@@@CM
)@@G@@TO THE ORIGINAL CALL MADE BY SNOBOL, IT SEEMS TO PRINT A FEW LINES@F@@@@CN
)@@G@@OF GARBAGE AND THEN DIE FROM A GUARD-MODE ERROR.  SOMETHING MAY BE@E@@@@CO
)@@G@@DONE ABOUT THIS IN THE FUTURE, BUT DON'T HOPE FOR TOO MUCH. @@@@@@@F@@@@CP
)@@G@@IT IS QUITE POSSIBLE TO WRITE EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS IN 1108 ASSEMBLY @G@@@@CQ
)@@G@@LANGUAGE.  A 'RELOCATABLE ELEMENT' IS CREATED BY @ASM, AND ANY LABEL    CR
)@@G@@@F@@@@THAT IS EXTERNALLY DEFINED IS AVAILABLE AS A FUNCTION NAME.  THE  CS
)@@G@@@G@@@@EXTERNAL TABLE AND COLLECTION ARE EXACTLY THE SAME AS DESCRIBED ABCT
)@@G@@OVE   @^@@@@FOR FORTRAN FUNCTIONS.  @@@@@@@F@@@@THE 'CALLING SEQUENCE' UCU
)@@G@@SED IS THAT OF FORTRAN, WHICH IS DESCRIBED@G@@@@HERE.  ON ENTRY TO THE FCV
)@@G@@UNCTION, REGISTER X11 WILL CONTAIN THE ADDRESS  @F@@@@OF THE FIRST WORD CW
)@@G@@OF A BLOCK OF PARAMETER ADDRESSES.  EACH WORD IN@G@@@@THIS BLOCK CONTAINCX
)@@G@@S THE ADDRESS OF A PARAMETER (OR THE FIRST WORD OF    @F@@@@THE PARAMETECY
)@@G@@R, IF MORE THAN ONE WORD IS REQUIRED).  THUS THE I-TH @E@@@@PARAMETER CACZ
)@@G@@N BE LOADED INTO REGISTER A0 BY THE FOLLOWING:  @E@@@@      LA    A0,I-1DA
)@@G@@,X11.            LOAD ADDR OF I-TH PARAM. @E@@@@      LA    A0,0,A0.    DB
)@@G@@           LOAD VALUE OF PARAM.     @G@@@@IF THERE ARE N PARAMETERS, THEDC
)@@G@@ WORD AT (N,X11) WILL BE A DUMMY WALK-    @F@@@@BACK WORD, AND THE WORD DD
)@@G@@AT (N+1,X11) WILL BE AN INSTRUCTION THAT  @G@@@@INITIATES THE RETURN MECDE
)@@G@@HANISM (CURRENTLY A JUMP).  THE RETURN VALUE    @F@@@@SHOULD BE PUT IN ADF
)@@G@@0 FOR A 'NORMAL' FORTRAN RETURN, WHICH WOULD BE @A@@@@DONE BY CODE LIKE DG
)@@G@@THE FOLLOWING:    @E@@@@      LA    A0,VALUE.              PUT RETURN VADH
)@@G@@LUE IN A0.  @B@@@@      J     N+1,X11.               RETURN.@F@@@@THE OTDI
)@@G@@HER RETURN FUNCTIONS CAN BE USED FROM AN ASSEMBLY-LANGUAGE  @A@@@@PROGRADJ
)@@G@@M BY CALLING THEM AS FOLLOWS: @E@@@@      J     RTNF.                  CDK
)@@G@@ALL RTNF (NO PARAMS).   @[@@@@.     @C@@@@      LMJ   X11,RTNI.         DL
)@@G@@     CALL RTNI(I) @D@@@@      +     I.                     ADDR OF PARAMDM
)@@G@@.     @[@@@@.     @C@@@@      LMJ   X11,RTNR.              CALL RTNR(R) DN
)@@G@@@#@@@@      +     R.    @[@@@@.     @D@@@@      LMJ   X11,RTNS.         DO
)@@G@@     CALL RTNS(S(1))    @#@@@@      +     S.    @@@@@@@G@@@@SOMETHING THDP
)@@G@@AT PERHAPS SHOULD BE POINTED OUT (EXPECIALLY FOR ASSEMBLY-  @G@@@@LANGUADQ
)@@G@@GE PROGRAMMERS) IS THAT WHENEVER A STRING IS PASSED ACROSS THIS   @G@@@@DR
)@@G@@INTERFACE, EITHER AS A PARAMETER OR A RETURN VALUE, THE SNOBOL CODE     DS
)@@G@@@G@@@@INVOLVED MAKES A COPY OF THE STRING.  THUS, FOR EXAMPLE, IF AN EXTDT
)@@G@@ERNAL @G@@@@FUNCTION RETURNS A STRING AND THIS STRING IS LATER PASSED BADU
)@@G@@CK AS AN    @G@@@@ARGUMENT TO THE SAME FUNCTION, IT WILL NOT REALLY BE TDV
)@@G@@HE 'SAME' STRING, @C@@@@BUT A DIFFERENT STRING WITH THE SAME VALUE.     DW
)@@G@@@@@@@@@G@@@@YET ANOTHER DETAIL IS THAT EXTERNAL FORTRAN FUNCTIONS SHOULDDX
)@@G@@ NOT BE     @G@@@@DECLARED AS 'SUBROUTINES', SINCE IN SNOBOL ALL FUNCTIODY
)@@G@@N MUST RETURN A   @G@@@@VALUE (EVEN IF IT IS NULL).  SUBROUTINES HAVEN'TDZ
)@@G@@ BEEN TRIED AS OF THIS  @G@@@@WRITING, SO IT ISN'T KNOWN JUST HOW THEY WEA
)@@G@@ILL BEHAVE, BUT IT CAN BE     @G@@@@EXPECTED THAT THEY WILL RETURN A RATEB
)@@G@@HER UNPREDICTABLE VALUE IF A NORMAL @G@@@@FORTRAN RETURN IS USED.  THEREEC
)@@G@@ SHOULDN'T BE ANY PROBLEMS WITH A SUBROU- @G@@@@TINE IF ANY OF THE SPECIED
)@@G@@AL SNOBOL RETURN FUNCTIONS ARE USED, BUT IS     @C@@@@IS PROBABLY SAFER EE
)@@G@@NOT TO USE SUBROUTINES AT ALL.@@@@@@@@@@@@@G@@@@************************EF

)@@G@@NG LIKE:    @^@@@@   @SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL   @ @@@@   @ADD  SNOBOL*LIB.<NAMGB
)@@G@@E>    @G@@@@IT MAY, OF COURSE, BE NECESSARY TO INSERT INITIALIZATION STAGC
)@@G@@TEMENTS     @G@[@@BETWEEN THESE TWO CARDS AND DATA AFTER THEM.  ALSO, THGD
)@@G@@E PROGRAM MAY OR  @F@@@[BETWEEN THESE TWO CARDS AND DATA AFTER THEM   ALGE
)@@G@@SO, SOME PROGRAMS @G@@@@MAY NOT CONTAIN AN END CARD--THE DOCUMENTATION SGF
)@@G@@HOULD TELL YOU SUCH     @G@@@@THINGS.  A DATA DECK CAN BE ADDED INTO THEGG

)@@G@@:     @ @@@@   @ADD  SNOBOL*LIB.<NAME>    @@@@@@@G@@@@LIBRARY FUNCTIONS GI
)@@G@@ARE STORED IN THREE ELEMENTS--DOCUMENTATION, INIT-    @G@@@@IALIZATION, GJ
)@@G@@AND FUNCTION CODE.  FOR A FUNCTION <NAME>, THE ELEMENTS     @#@@@@WOULD GK
)@@G@@BE NAMED:   @^@@@@   SNOBOL*LIB.<NAME>-D  @^@@@@   SNOBOL*LIB.<NAME>-I  GL
)@@G@@@^@@@@   SNOBOL*LIB.<NAME>-F  @G@@@@THE INITIALIZATION ELEMENT CONTAINS GM
)@@G@@ANYTHING NECESSARY TO 'SET UP' THE  @G@@@@FUNCTION(S) IN THE PACKAGE, ANGN
)@@G@@D WILL HAVE TO BE EXECUTED ONCE AT THE    @G@@@@START OF A RUN.  THE FUNGO
)@@G@@CTIONAL ELEMENT IS NEVER TRANSFERRED TO, BUT    @G@@@@IS ONLY ENTERED BYGP
)@@G@@ MEANS OF FUNCTION CALLS.  IT IS CONCEIVABLE THAT     @G@@@@A PACKAGE COGQ
)@@G@@ULD CONTAIN ONLY INITIALIZATION AND NO FUNCTIONS, AND IF    @G@@@@SUCH AGR
)@@G@@ THING SHOWS UP, IT WILL PROBABLY HAVE A FUNCTIONAL ELEMENT THAT  @G@@@@GS
)@@G@@CONSISTS OF A SINGLE COMMENT CARD, SO THE '-F' ELEMENT CAN BE INCLUDED  GT
)@@G@@@G@@@@FOR ALL PACKAGES WITHOUT WORRYING ABOUT THE EXEC KILLING THE RUN BGU
)@@G@@ECAUSE@G@@@@AN @ADD CARD WAS USED WITH A NON-EXISTENT ELEMENT NAME.  ALLGV
)@@G@@ THREE OF   @G@@@@THE ELEMENTS CAN BE INCLUDED IN A PROGRAM BY USING AN GW
)@@G@@@ADD CARD, SINCE  @G@@@@THE DOCUMENTATION ELEMENTS WILL HAVE A '*' IN COGX
)@@G@@LUMN 1 OF EACH CARD IN  @G@@@@CASE SOMEONE WANTS THE DOCUMENTATION TO BEGY
)@@G@@ LISTED IN HIS PROGRAM ALONG  @ @@@@WITH THE ROUTINES BEING USED. @@@@@@GZ
)@@G@@@G@@@[SINCE EVERYTHING BUT THE SNOBOL4 EXECUTIVE IS IN SYMBOLIC FORM, USHA
)@@G@@ERS   @G@@@[CAN QUITE EASILY GET LISTINGS OF ANYTHING IN THIS LIBRARY, SHB
)@@G@@IMPLY BY    @G@@@[REFERENCING THE ELEMENTS, USING THE NAMING CONVENTIONSHC
)@@G@@ DESCRIBED ABOVE. @G@@@[FOR EXAMPLE, TO GET A LISTING OF THE DOCUMENTATIHD
)@@G@@ON, INITIALIZATION,     @E@@@[AND FUNCTION CODE FOR THE 'QUICKSORT' PACKHE
)@@G@@AGE, YOU COULD DO:@A@@@[   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.QUICKSORT-D     @A@@@[   @ELHF
)@@G@@T  SNOBOL*LIB.QUICKSORT-I     @A@@@[   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.QUICKSORT-F     HG
)@@G@@@F@@@[TO GET A PUNCHED COPY, THE 'ELT' SHOULD BE REPLACED BY '@PCH,S'.  HH
)@@G@@@@@@@[@G@@@[************************************************************HI
)@@G@@************@C@@@[OTHER CONVENTIONS USED IN THE SNOBOL4 LIBRARY:  @@@@@[HJ
)@@G@@@G@@@@TO MAKE SURE THAT DIFFERENT LIBRARY ROUTINES CAN BE USED IN THE SAHK
)@@G@@ME    @G@@@@PROGRAM, IT IS NECESSARY TO PREVENT THEM FROM USING THE SAMEHL
)@@G@@ LABELS,    @G@@@@FUNCTION NAMES, AND GLOBAL VARIABLE NAMES.  THE EASIESHM
)@@G@@T WAY TO DO THIS  @G@@@@IS TO MAKE EACH START WITH A STRING UNIQUE TO THHN
)@@G@@E PACKAGE--THAT IS,     @G@@@@MAKE EACH START WITH <NAME> OR SOME SHORTEHO
)@@G@@R 'ABBREVIATED' FORM OF <NAME>@G@@@@THAT IS UNLIKELY TO BE DUPLICATED INHP
)@@G@@ OTHER PACKAGES.  IN ANY CASE, THE  @F@@@@DOCUMENTATION ELEMENT SHOULD SHQ
)@@G@@AY HOW THIS PROBLEM IS HANDLED.     @@@@@@@G@@@@THERE SHOULD BE, OF COURHR
)@@G@@SE, AN EXPLICIT LIST OF ALL VARIABLES THAT THE  @G@@@@USER CAN DEFINE FOHS
)@@G@@R THE PACKAGE.  IT IS PROBABLY A GOOD IDEA TO ASSIGN  @E@@@@DEFAULT VALUHT
)@@G@@ES TO ANY SUCH VARIABLES WITH STATEMENTS LIKE:  @^@@@@   X  =  IDENT(X) HU
)@@G@@ 50   @G@@@@WHICH WILL ASSIGN A VALUE TO X IF NO EARLIER STATEMENT HAS DHV
)@@G@@ONE SO.     @@@@@@@F@@@@THE DOCUMENTATION ELEMENT SHOULD CONTAIN AN INDIHW
)@@G@@CATION OF WHAT    @F@@@@VERSION OF SNOBOL4 WAS USED TO DEBUG THE PACKAGEHX
)@@G@@, IN CASE FUTURE  @C@@@@CHANGES IN THE LANGUAGE INTRODUCE NEW BUGS.     HY
)@@G@@@@@@@@@G@@@@ANOTHER USEFUL THING IS TO MAKE EACH ELEMENT IDENTIFY ITSELFHZ
)@@G@@.  THIS     @G@@@@CAN BE DONE BY MAKING THE FIRST LINE A COMMENT CONTAINIA
)@@G@@ING THE NAME OF   @]@@@@THE ELEMENT.@@@@@@@G@@@@THE DOCUMENTATION ELEMENIB
)@@G@@T SHOULD CONTAIN THE NAME OF ITS AUTHOR(S) AND  @G@@@@AN INDICATION OF HIC
)@@G@@OW TO GET IN TOUCH WITH THEM.  THIS HAS TWO BASIC     @G@@@@PURPOSES:  IID
)@@G@@T TELLS USERS WHO TO GO TO IF THEY HAVE PROBLEMS WITH A     @F@@@@PACKAGIE
)@@G@@E OR BUGS APPEAR IN THE CODE; IT ALSO BRINGS THE NAME OF THE@G@@@@PROGRAIF
)@@G@@MMER TO THE ATTENTION OF PEOPLE INTERESTED IN THE THINGS HE IS    @G@@@@IG
)@@G@@WORKING WITH--PROVIDING BOTH PUBLICITY AND THE POSSIBILITY OF MORE JOB  IH
)@@G@@@ @@@@OFFERS IF THE CODE IS GOOD.   @@@@@@@G@@@@************************II

)@@G@@ONS.  @@@@@A@#@@@#1.3.1. FORMATS.   @G@@@#   THE FORMATS USED WITH OUTPUMP
)@@G@@T() ARE NOW THE WAY THEY ARE DESCRIBED    @G@@@#IN THE USERS MANUAL.  THMQ
)@@G@@AT IS, STRINGS ARE PRINTED UNDER AN 'A1' SPEC-  @G@@@#IFICATION, RATHER MR
)@@G@@THAN 'A6'.  THUS, THE STANDARD OUTPUT STRINGS, OUTPUT @E@@@#AND PUNCH, AMS
)@@G@@CT AS IF THE PROGRAM HAD EXECUTED THE FOLLOWING:@@@@@#@B@@@#      OUTPUTMT
)@@G@@('OUTPUT',6,'(1X,131A1)')     @A@@@#      OUTPUT('PUNCH',1,'(80A1)')    MU
)@@G@@@@@@@#@ @@@#1.3.2. PATTERN FUNCTIONS.     @G@@@#   SPAN() NOW WORKS CORRMV
)@@G@@ECTLY WHEN IT SHOULD MATCH A FINAL SUBSTRING.   @@@@@#@G@@@#   ALL OF THMW
)@@G@@E PATTERN-VALUED FUNCTION (ANY, ARBNO, BREAK, LEN, NOTANY,  @G@@@#POS, RMX
)@@G@@POS, SPAN, TAB) NOW CHECK THEIR ARGUMENTS WHEN THEY ARE CALLED,   @G@@@#MY
)@@G@@WITH THE OBVIOUS EXCEPTION FOR ARGUMENTS OF TYPE 'EXPRESSION'.  THE     MZ
)@@G@@@G@@@#CHECKING WAS PREVIOUSLY DONE DURING THE PATTERN MATCH.  THIS SPEEDNA
)@@G@@S UP  @E@@@#PATTERN MATCHING SOMEWHAT, BUT MEANS THAT STATEMENTS LIKE   NB
)@@G@@@@@@@#@^@@@#      P  =  LEN('A')    @@@@@#@G@@@#WILL CAUSE AN ERROR (SEENC
)@@G@@ SEC. 4.2.3), WHILE FORMERLY SUCH STATEMENTS    @F@@@#WOULD SUCCEED, ANDND
)@@G@@ AN ERROR WOULD OCCUR ONLY WHEN P WAS USED IN A @#@@@#PATTERN MATCH.    NE
)@@G@@@@@@@#@G@@@#   THE HEURISTICS USED IN THE QUICKSCAN MODE HAVE BEEN IMPRONF
)@@G@@VED, AND    @G@@@#AS A RESULT SOME PATTERN MATCHES WILL FAIL SOONER THANNG
)@@G@@ BEFORE.  THIS    @G@@@#MAY PRODUCE CHANGES IF IMMEDIATE ASSIGNMENT IS UNH
)@@G@@SED IN PATTERN MATCHES  @]@@@#THAT FAIL.  @@@@@#@I@@@#******************NI
)@@G@@**************************************************************    @ @@@#NJ
)@@G@@2. EXECUTIVE CONTROL CARDS.   @G@@@#   THERE ARE A LOT OF CONTROL CARDS NK

)@@G@@ DESCRIBE HERE ONLY THE CARDS THAT  @B@@@#PERTAIN SPECIFICALLY TO A SNOBNN
)@@G@@OL JOB.     @@@@@#@A@@@#   THE FIRST CARD IN A DECK MUST BE:@@@@@#@E@@@#NO
)@@G@@      @RUN  <NAME>,<PROJ>,<USER>,<TIME>,<PAGES>/<CARDS>     @@@@@#@D@@@#NP
)@@G@@THE VARIABLE ITEMS SURROUNDED BY '<' AND '>' ARE:     @@@@@#@D@@@#<NAME>NQ
)@@G@@ CAN BE ANY NAME--IT IS USUALLY THE USER'S NAME @A@@@#<PROJ> IS THE USERNR
)@@G@@'S PROJECT NUMBER.@A@@@#<USER> IS THE USER'S I.D. NUMBER.   @F@@@#<TIME>NS
)@@G@@ IS THE TIME LIMIT FOR THE RUN.  A LIMIT OF 5 MINUTES AND 30@F@@@#   SECNT
)@@G@@ONDS WOULD BE WRITTEN AS '5M30S'.  EITHER THE MINUTE OR THE @F@@@#   SECNU
)@@G@@OND PART CAN BE OMITTED.  A SINGLE INTEGER IS ASSUMED TO BE @F@@@#   MINNV
)@@G@@UTES.  IF <TIME> IS OMITTED ENTIRELY, IT DEFAULTS TO '10S'. @C@@@    SEENW
)@@G@@ SECTION 4.1.1 FOR THE SNOBOL4 TIME LIMIT.@G@@@#<PAGES> IS THE MAXIMUM NNX
)@@G@@UMBER OF PAGES THAT CAN BE PRINTED.  IF OMITTED,@^@@@#   '30' IS ASSUMEDNY
)@@G@@.     @G@@@#<CARDS> IS THE MAXIMUM NUMBER OF CARDS THAT CAN BE PUNCHED. NZ
)@@G@@ THE DEFAULT@#@@@#   VALUE IS 200.  @@@@@#@B@ @#   THE LAST CARD IN A DEOA
)@@G@@CK SHOULD BE:     @@@ @#@]@ @#      @FIN  @@@ @#@A@@@ THE LAST CARD IN AOB
)@@G@@ DECK SHOULD BE:  @]@@@    @FIN     @G@@@#THOUGH THIS REALLY ISN'T NEEDEOC
)@@G@@D, IT IS ADVISABLE TO USE IT.  THIS IS    @G@@@#BECAUSE THE LAST CARD INOD
)@@G@@ A DECK HAS A WAY OF GETTING LOST IN ALL THE    @G@@@#HANDLING INVOLVED OE
)@@G@@IN RUNNING IT ON THE COMPUTER, AND NOTHING IS HURT    @ @@@#IF A @FIN CAOF
)@@G@@RD DISAPPEARS.    @@@@@#@G@@@#BETWEEN THESE TWO CARDS, AS MANY SNOBOL4 POG
)@@G@@ROGRAMS CAN BE RUN AS DESIRED,@E@@@#BY PRECEDING EACH PROGRAM BY EITHER OH
)@@G@@OF THE FOLLOWING CARDS: @]@@@#   @SNOBOL  @^@@@#   @SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL   OI
)@@G@@@G@@@#IF THESE TWO VERSIONS OF SNOBOL DIFFER, THE SECOND ONE WILL BE THEOJ
)@@G@@ MOST @F@@@#RECENT.  MOST OF THE EXAMPLES GIVEN BELOW WILL USE THE SECONOK
)@@G@@D.    @@@@@#@G@A@#   IT IS POSSIBLE TO USE MASS STORAGE ('FASTRAND') DATOL

)@@G@@******************************@ @A@#3. DIFFERENCES FROM MANUAL.   @^@A@#PJ
)@@G@@3.1. CHARACTER SET.     @G@A@#   THE FOLLOWING CHARACTERS ARE DIFFERENT PK
)@@G@@FROM THE ONES USED IN THE     @^@A@#SNOBOL4 USERS MANUAL:   @^@@@A3. 110PL
)@@G@@8 CHARACTER SET.  @@@@@A@G@@@ATHERE ARE A NUMBER OF CHARACTERS USED IN TPM
)@@G@@HE MANUAL THAT ARE DIFFERENT  @G@@@AON THE 1108 OR HAVE ALTERNATE CHARACPN
)@@G@@TERS THAT CAN BE USED.  A SLIGHT    @G@@@APROBLEM IS CREATED BY THE USE PO
)@@G@@OF SEVERAL DIFFERENT CHARACTER SETS ON    @G@@@ADIFFERENT 1108 LINE PRINPP
)@@G@@TERS.  TO MAKE SENSE OF THE FOLLOWING LIST,     @G@@@AYOU SHOULD HAVE THPQ
)@@G@@IS PRINTED ON A PRINTER WITH A COMPLETE CHARACTER     @G@@@ASET.  IF YOUPR
)@@G@@ CAN'T, THE CARD-PUNCH CODES MAY BE OF HELP.  THE IMPORTANT @B@@@ACHARACPS
)@@G@@TER DIFFERENCES FROM THE MANUAL ARE:@B@@@#   MANUAL:         1108:     PPT
)@@G@@UNCHES:     @A@@@#   DOUBLE QUOTE    '^'       11-7-8 @E@@@#   OR-OPERATPU
)@@G@@OR     '!'       11-0 (MUST BE MULTI-PUNCHED)   @C@@@#   LEFT BRACKET   PV
)@@G@@ '<', '['  12-6-8, 12-5-8     @B@@@#   RIGHT BRACKET   '>', ']'  6-8, 11PW
)@@G@@-5-8  @A@@@#   NOT-OPERATOR    '\'       0-6-8  @A@@@#   EXPONENTIATION PX
)@@G@@ '", '**'  0-7-8  @@@@@#@G@@@#THE 029 KEYPUNCHES LACK THE '?', WHICH MUSPY
)@@G@@T BE MULTI-PUNCHED AS 12-0.   @@@@@#@G@@@#   AN IDENTIFIER CAN CONTAIN TPZ
)@@G@@HE CHARACTERS PERIOD ('.'), MINUS ('-'),  @G@@@#AND DOLLAR SIGN ('$') INQA
)@@G@@ ADDITION TO LETTERS AND DIGITS.  OF COURSE,    @F@@@#THE FIRST CHARACTEQB
)@@G@@R OF AN IDENTIFIER MUST BE A LETTER, AS USUAL.  @G@@@#NOTE THAT THE 'EXTQC
)@@G@@RA' CHARACTERS THAT CAN BE USED WILL VARY BETWEEN     @G@@@#DIFFERENT COQD
)@@G@@MPUTERS.  ALL OF THEM ALLOW THE USE OF LETTERS, DIGITS, AND @D@@@#PERIODQE
)@@G@@S.  SOME VALID IDENTIFIERS ON THE 1108 ARE:     @@@@@#@]@@@#      I     QF
)@@G@@@]@@@#      X1    @#@@@#      REST.MASS   @#@@@#      NET-PROFIT  @#@@@#QG
)@@G@@      SYS$.LIB$   @#@@@#      A-$7.48     @]@@@#      GAMMA @#@@@#      QH
)@@G@@GAMMA-RAY   @@@@@#@E@@@#   A CONTINUATION CARD CAN START WITH '.', '+', QI
)@@G@@OR ','.     @@@@@#@G@@@#   A LABEL MUST START WITH A LETTER OR DIGIT, BUQJ
)@@G@@T SUBSEQUENT CHARACTERS @G@@@#CAN BE ANYTHING BUT A BLANK.  A LABEL IN AQK
)@@G@@ GO-TO FIELD OF AN INSTRUCTION@G@@@#MUST AS USUAL SATISFY THE RULES FOR QL
)@@G@@AN IDENTIFIER, AND ANY OTHER LABELS @G@@@#THAT AREN'T VALID IDENTIFIERS QM
)@@G@@MUST BE TRANSFERRED TO INDIRECTLY.  THUS, @G@@@#WHILE 'L7,A#B' IS A VALIQN
)@@G@@D LABEL, :S(L7,A#B) WILL RESULT IN AN ERROR     @G@@@#MESSAGE--IT MUST BQO
)@@G@@E :S($'L7,A#B').  NOTE ESPECIALLY THAT NUMBERS ARE    @D@@@#VALID LABELSQP
)@@G@@, BUT CAN'T BE TRANSFERRED TO DIRECTLY.   @@@@@#@G@@@#******************QQ

)@@G@@@#@@@#4. NEW THINGS.    @@@@@A@^@@@#4.1. 1108 ADDITIONS.    @G@@@A   THEQT
)@@G@@SE ARE THINGS THAT ARE ONLY AVAILABLE ON THIS IMPLEMENTATION OF   @F@@@AQU
)@@G@@SNOBOL; PROGRAMS THAT USE THEM MAY HAVE PROBLEMS ON OTHER SYSTEMS.@@@@@AQV
)@@G@@@#@@@#4.1.1. &TIMELIMIT @F@@@#   A SNOBOL4 TIME LIMIT HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTQW
)@@G@@ED ON THE 1108 AS A NEW @F@@@#KEYWORD, &TIMELIMIT.  ITS VALUE IS THE NUMQX
)@@G@@BER OF MILLISECONDS THAT@F@ @#THE PROGRAM IS TO ALLOWED FOR EXECUTION.  QY
)@@G@@THAT IS, WHEN GE(TIME(),@F@ @#&TIMELIMIT) SUCCEEDS, THE PROGRAM WILL BE QZ
)@@G@@TERMINATED ABNORMALLY.  @G@@@ ARE ALLOWED FOR EXECUTION.  THAT IS, WHEN RA
)@@G@@GE(TIME(),&TIMELIMIT) SUCCEEDS@B@@@ THE PROGRAM WILL BE TERMINATED ABNORRB
)@@G@@MALLY.@G@@@#   NOTE THAT THIS IS QUITE DIFFERENT FROM THE TIME LIMIT ON RC
)@@G@@THE @RUN    @G@@@#CONTROL CARD.  THE LATTER REFERS TO THE TOTAL TIME FORRD
)@@G@@ ALL PROGRAMS IN  @G@@@#A RUN; EXCEEDING IT CAUSES THE ENTIRE RUN TO DIERE
)@@G@@.  &TIMELIMIT REFERS    @F@@@#ONLY TO THE EXECUTION TIME FOR A SINGLE SNRF
)@@G@@OBOL4 PROGRAM; EXCEEDING@G@@@#IT CAUSES ONLY THAT ONE PROGRAM TO ABORT, RG
)@@G@@AND THE NEXT PROGRAM IS THEN  @G@@@#STARTED.  THUS A SET OF SNOBOL PROGRRH
)@@G@@AMS CAN BE RUN TOGETHER, AND EACH   @F@@@#CAN HAVE ITS OWN TIME LIMIT.  RI
)@@G@@THE LIMIT ON THE @RUN CARD SHOULD BE@G@@@#BIG ENOUGH TO INCLUDE COMPILATRJ
)@@G@@ION AND EXECUTION OF ALL PROGRAMS IN THE  @[@@@#RUN.  @G@@@#   IF NO VALRK
)@@G@@UE IS ASSIGNED TO &TIMELIMIT, IT WILL BE 5 SECONDS LESS THAN@G@@@#WHAT RRL
)@@G@@EMAINS OF THE LIMIT ON THE @RUN CARD WHEN THE PROGRAM STARTS ITS  @G@@@#RM
)@@G@@EXECUTION.  THIS ALLOWS TIME FOR AT LEAST PART OF A DUMP IF &DUMP IS    RN
)@@G@@@G@@@#SET AND THE TIME LIMIT IS EXCEEDED.  FOR PROGRAMS WITH A LOT OF DARO
)@@G@@TA,   @F@@@#IT MAY BE NECESSARY TO DECREASE THE TIME LIMIT A BIT MORE TORP
)@@G@@ GET A@#@@@#COMPLETE DUMP.    @G@@@#   AS AN EXAMPLE, THE FOLLOWING PROGRQ
)@@G@@RAM WILL DIE AFTER 20 MILLISECONDS: @@@@@#@[@@@#*     @ @@@#*  PROGRAM TRR
)@@G@@O TEST &TIMELIMIT @[@@@#*     @^@@@#   &TIMELIMIT  =  20    @#@@@#L     RS
)@@G@@      :(L)  @[@@@#END   @@@@@#@G@@@#************************************RT
)@@G@@************************************@^@@@#4.1.2. SNOBOL LIBRARY.  @@@@@#RU

)@@G@@@^@@@#THE FOLLOWING CARD:     @ @@@#   @ELT  SNOBOL*LIB.DOCUMENT  @@@@@#RX

)@@G@@******@ @@@A4.1.3. EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS.    @@@@@A@G@@@AIT IS NOW POSSIBLERZ
)@@G@@ TO USE FUNCTIONS WRITTEN IN FORTRAN OR 1108 ASSEMBLY @G@@@ALANGUAGE WITSA
)@@G@@H A SNOBOL PROGRAM.  THIS 'EXTERNAL FUNCTION' FACILITY IS   @E@@@ADESCRISB
)@@G@@BED IS A SEPARATE DOCUMENT, WHICH CAN BE PRINTED BY:  @ @@@A   @ELT  SNOSC
)@@G@@BOL*LIB.EXTERNAL-D@@@@@A@G@@@A******************************************SD
)@@G@@******************************@A@@@A4.1.4. NEW INTRINSIC FUNCTIONS.     SE
)@@G@@@@@@@A@^@@@A4.1.4.1. ASSIGN(N,V).   @@@@@A@G@@@ATHIS ASSIGNS THE VALUE OSF
)@@G@@F V TO THE NAME N, JUST LIKE THE STATEMENT:     @]@@@A   N  =  V  @F@@@ASG
)@@G@@THE VALUE OF V IS RETURNED AS THE VALUE OF ASSIGN(N,V).  THUS THIS@G@@@ASH
)@@G@@FUNCTION CAN BE USED TO DO AN ASSIGNMENT OF A PART OF AN EXPRESSION,    SI
)@@G@@@[@@@AAS IN:@^@@@A   X  =  ASSIGN(I,X) + 1@B@@@AWHICH IS EQUIVALENT TO TSJ
)@@G@@HE TWO STATEMENTS:@]@@@A   I  =  X  @#@@@A   X  =  X + 1    @G@@@ABUT TASK
)@@G@@KES ABOUT HALF AS MUCH TIME TO EXECUTE.  IT IS OFTEN USEFUL TO    @C@@@ASL
)@@G@@DEFINE AN OPERATOR THAT INVOKES ASSIGN(), AS:   @^@@@A   OPSYN('#','ASSISM
)@@G@@GN',2)@#@@@ATHEN THE STATEMENT@ @@@A   X  =  (Y # 1)  +  (Z # 2)  @G@@@ASN
)@@G@@WILL SET Y TO 1, Z TO 2, AND X TO 3 (IN THAT ORDER).  ASSIGN() CAN BE   SO
)@@G@@@G@@@AGENERALLY EXPECTED TO BEHAVE EXACTLY LIKE THE EQUIVALENT ASSIGNMENSP
)@@G@@T     @G@@@ASTATEMENT, SINCE THEY ARE BOTH HANDLED BY THE SAME CODE INTESQ
)@@G@@RNALLY.     @@@@@A@G@@@A************************************************SR
)@@G@@************************@B@@@A4.1.5. LIBERALIZED INTRINSIC FUNCTIONS.   SS
)@@G@@@@@@@A@G@@@ATHE RESTRICTION THAT MOST INTRINSIC FUNCTIONS BE CALLED WITHST
)@@G@@ EXACTLY THE@G@@@A'RIGHT' NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS IS IN THE PROCESS OF BEINGSU
)@@G@@ RELAXED.  THE    @G@@@ACODE TO MAKE THEM BEHAVE IN THIS RESPECT LIKE USSV
)@@G@@ER-DEFINED FUNCTIONS    @G@@@AHAS BEEN WRITTEN; IT IS NECESSARY TO REWRISW
)@@G@@TE EACH INTRINSIC TO USE THE  @H@@@ANEW CODE, SO THIS WILL BE A CONTINUISX
)@@G@@NG PROCESS, AFFECTING A FEW FUNCTIONS     @G@@@AAT A TIME.  AT THE SAME SY
)@@G@@TIME, SOME FUNCTIONS WILL BE MADE MORE GENERAL, @G@@@ASO THEY WILL USE ASZ
)@@G@@NY EXTRA ARGUMENTS THEY ARE GIVEN.  THE FUNCTIONS THAT@C@@@AHAVE BEEN RETA
)@@G@@WRITTEN THIS WAY CURRENTLY INCLUDE: @@@@@A@D@@@AASSIGN(N,V) EVALUATES ANTB
)@@G@@D IGNORES EXTRA ARGUMENTS.    @C@@@ADATE() EVALUATES AND IGNORES ANY ARGTC
)@@G@@UMENTS.     @C@@@ADUMP(N) EVALUATES AND IGNORES EXTRA ARGUMENTS.  @G@@@ATD
)@@G@@IDENT(P1,P2,...,PN) SUCCEEDS IF ALL OF ITS ARGUMENTS ARE IDENTICAL.     TE
)@@G@@@F@@@A   IDENT(P1) MEANS IDENT(P1,''); IDENT() IS EQUIVALENT TO ''.     TF
)@@G@@@C@@@ATIME() EVALUATES AND IGNORES ANY ARGUMENTS.     @@@@@A@G@@@A******TG
)@@G@@******************************************************************@G@@@#TH

)@@G@@@ @@@#4.2. VERSION 3 ADDITIONS.     @G@@@#   THE THINGS DESCRIBED IN THITJ
)@@G@@S SECTION ARE ADDITIONS TO THE SNOBOL4    @G@@@#LANGUAGE THAT ARE AVAILATK
)@@G@@BLE ON ANY COMPUTER FOR WHICH VERSION 3 HAS BEEN@G@@@#IMPLEMENTED.  THISTL
)@@G@@ INCLUDES MOST OF THE LARGER SYSTEMS BY NOW.  USERS   @G@@@#WHOSE MANUALTM
)@@G@@S STATE THAT THEY ARE FOR VERSION 3 CAN IGNORE THIS SECTION,@G@@@#UNLESSTN
)@@G@@ THEY WOULD LIKE TO KNOW WHAT WON'T WORK IF THEY RUN THEIR PROG-  @G@@@#TO
)@@G@@RAMS UNDER VERSION 2.  SEE ALSO SECTION 1.3, WHICH DESCRIBES CHANGES    TP
)@@G@@@B@@@#TO FEATURES THAT EXISTED IN VERSION 2.    @@@@@#@#@@@#4.2.1. TABLETQ
)@@G@@S.    @G@@@#   A NEW DATA TYPE HAS BEEN ADDED, 'TABLE'.  A TABLE ACTS BATR
)@@G@@SICALLY LIKE@G@@@#A ONE-DIMENSIONAL ARRAY WHICH WILL ACCEPT ANY DATA OBJTS
)@@G@@ECT AS A SUB-     @G@@@#SCRIPT.  IT IS VERY CONVENIENT FOR BUILDING SYMBTT
)@@G@@OL TABLES, ASSOCIATIONS,@G@@@#OR WHATEVER YOU LIKE TO CALL THEM.  A TABLTU
)@@G@@E IS CREATED BY A CALL OF:    @@@@@#@#@@@#      TABLE(M,N)  @@@@@#@G@@@#TV
)@@G@@WHERE M IS THE INITIAL SIZE OF THE TABLE, AND N IS THE AMOUNT TO EXPAND TW
)@@G@@@ @@@#IT BY IF IT GETS FILLED.  THUS@@@@@#@ @@@#      T  =  TABLE(100,25TX
)@@G@@)     @@@@@#@G@@@#WILL ASSIGN TO T A TABLE WITH ROOM FOR 100 ENTRIES INITY
)@@G@@TIALLY.  IF THIS  @G@@@#ISN'T BIG ENOUGH, T WILL BE EXPANDED TO 125 ENTRTZ
)@@G@@IES, AND IF THIS IS     @G@@@#FILLED, TO 150 ENTRIES, THEN TO 175, ETC. UA
)@@G@@ M AND N CAN BOTH BE OMITTED, @G@@@#IN WHICH CASE A DEFAULT VALUE OF 10 UB
)@@G@@IS USED.  THUS, TABLE(15) IS EQUIV- @F@@@#ALENT TO TABLE(15,10), AND TABUC
)@@G@@LE() IS EQUIVALENT TO TABLE(10,10). @E@@@#   A TABLE IS TREATED MUCH LIKUD
)@@G@@E AN ARRAY.  FOR EXAMPLE,     @@@@@#@#@@@#      T<'A'>  =  3@@@@@#@G@@@#UE
)@@G@@ASSIGNS THE VALUE 3 TO THE 'A'-TH ELEMENT OF T.  THE SUBSCRIPT MAY BE   UF
)@@G@@@G@@@#OF ANY TYPE WHATSOEVER, INCLUDING ARRAYS, PATTERNS, TABLES, AND PRUG
)@@G@@OGRAM-@G@@@#DEFINED TYPES.  IF A SUBSCRIPT IS USED FOR WHICH NO ENTRY EXUH
)@@G@@ISTS, ONE   @G@@@#IS CREATED AND GIVEN A NULL VALUE.  THERE IS NOTHING TUI
)@@G@@HAT CORRESPONDS   @G@@@#TO THE FAILURE OF AN ARRAY REFERENCE BECAUSE THEUJ
)@@G@@ INDEX IS OUT OF BOUNDS.@B@@@#IF T IS A TABLE, T<X> WILL ALWAYS SUCCEED.UK
)@@G@@@G@@@#   PROGRAMMERS ARE CAUTIONED THAT NO TYPE CONVERSIONS ARE DONE ON UL
)@@G@@THE   @G@@@#SUBSCRIPT USED WITH A TABLE.  THUS T<1>, T<'1'>, T<'01'>, ANUM
)@@G@@D T<1.0>    @G@@@#REFERENCE DIFFERENT ITEMS IN T.  PARTICULAR CARE IS NEUN
)@@G@@EDED WHEN THE     @G@@@#SUBSCRIPT IS THE RESULT OF AN EXPRESSION.  SNOBOUO
)@@G@@L4'S AUTOMATIC TYPE     @G@@@#CONVERSIONS CAN PRODUCE UNEXPECTED RESULTSUP
)@@G@@ IF YOU AREN'T CAREFUL TO     @F@@@#ENSURE THAT THE EXPRESSION PRODUCES UQ
)@@G@@AN OBJECT OF THE CORRECT TYPE.@G@@@#   THE FUNCTION ITEM(T,X) WILL WORK UR
)@@G@@FOR TABLES, AND WILL PRODUCE T<X>.  @F@@@#HOWEVER, COPY(T) WILL NOT YET US
)@@G@@ACCEPT TABLES.  ALSO, THE UNARY NAME@G@@@#OPERATOR, '.', CAN'T BE USED OUT
)@@G@@N TABLE REFERENCES YET.  THAT IS, .T<X>   @E@@@#WILL PRODUCE AN ERROR (SUU
)@@G@@EE SEC. 4.2.3) IF T IS A TABLE.     @G@@@#   CONVERSION BETWEEN TABLES AUV
)@@G@@ND ARRAYS CAN BE DONE BY USING CONVERT(). @#@@@#IF T IS A TABLE,  @@@@@#UW
)@@G@@@ @@@#      A  =  CONVERT(T,'ARRAY')@@@@@#@G@@@#ASSIGNS TO A AN ARRAY WIUX
)@@G@@TH PROTOTYPE 'N,2', WHERE N IS THE NUMBER OF    @G@@@#NON-NULL ITEMS IN UY
)@@G@@T.  FOR EACH I WITHIN THE RANGE [1,N], A<I,1> WILL    @G@@@#BE AN OBJECTUZ
)@@G@@ THAT HAS BEEN USED AS A SUBSCRIPT FOR T, AND A<I,2> WILL   @G@@@#BE THEVA
)@@G@@ VALUE ASSOCIATED WITH THAT OBJECT.  THE ORDER OF THE ITEMS WILL  @G@@@#VB
)@@G@@BE UNPREDICTABLE.  ONLY ITEMS WITH NON-NULL VALUES WILL BE INCLUDED; IF VC
)@@G@@@C@@@#THERE IS NO SUCH ITEM, THE CONVERSION FAILS.    @G@@@#   A 2-DIMENVD
)@@G@@SIONAL ARRAY WHOSE SECOND SUBSCRIPT HAS A RANGE OF TWO CAN  @G@@@#BE CONVE
)@@G@@VERTED TO A TABLE.  FOR EXAMPLE, IF R IS AN ARRAY WITH PROTOTYPE  @#@@@#VF
)@@G@@'M,N:2', THEN     @@@@@#@ @@@#      B  =  CONVERT(R,'TABLE')@@@@@#@E@@@#VG
)@@G@@WILL ASSIGN TO B A TABLE AS IF THE FOLLOWING HAD BEEN DONE: @@@@@#@ @@@#VH
)@@G@@      B  =  TABLE(N - M + 1)  @#@@@#      I  =  M     @ @@@#L     B< R<IVI
)@@G@@,1> >  =  R<I,2>  @B@@@#      I  =  LT(I,N)   I + 1       :S(L)   @@@@@#VJ
)@@G@@@G@@@ FOR AN EXAMPLE OF THE USE OF TABLES, IF STRINGS OF ZEROES AND ONESVK
)@@G@@ ARE  @G@@@ BEING USED TO REPRESENT BINARY NUMBERS, AND YOU WANT TO STORVL
)@@G@@E SOME OF   @F@@@ THE BINARY NUMBERS AS OCTAL NUMBERS FOR COMPACTNESS, YVM
)@@G@@OU WILL NEED@G@@@ ROUTINES TO TRANSLATE BETWEEN THE TWO REPRESENTATIONS.VN
)@@G@@  THE FOLLOWING   @G@@@ TWO FUNCTIONS, BINARY(X) AND OCTAL(X), COULD BE VO
)@@G@@USED FOR THIS.  FIRST,  @F@@@ IT IS NECESSARY TO SET THEM UP--NOTE THE UVP
)@@G@@SE OF THE TABLE BINOCT. @[@@@    *  @ @@@       BINOCT  =  TABLE(8)     VQ
)@@G@@@ @@@       OCTBIN  =  ARRAY('0:7') @D@@@       TEMP  =  '00000011010201VR
)@@G@@131004101511061117'     @D@@@    L  TEMP  LEN(3) . I  LEN(1) . J  =     VS
)@@G@@       :F(M)@^@@@       BINOCT<I>  =  J   @D@@@       OCTBIN<J>  =  I   VT
)@@G@@                         :(L) @ @@@    M  DEFINE('BINARY(S)I')    @ @@@ VU
)@@G@@      DEFINE('OCTAL(S)I')     @[@@@    *  @G@@@ THE FUNCTIONS ARE THEN DVV
)@@G@@EFINED AS FOLLOWS.  NOTE THAT THEY BOTH FAIL    @B@@@ IF THE ARGUMENT HAVW
)@@G@@S INVALID CHARACTERS.   @[@@@    *  @E@@@    BINARY  S  LEN(1) . I  =   VX
)@@G@@                   :F(RETURN) @G@@@       BINARY  =  BINARY  OCTBIN<I>  VY
)@@G@@             :F(FRETURN)S(BINARY)   @[@@@    *  @E@@@    OCTAL  EQ(REMDRVZ
)@@G@@(SIZE(S),3),0)                 :S(OCTAL1) @C@@@       S  =  DUPL('0',3 -WA
)@@G@@ REMDR(SIZE(S),3))  S   @E@@@    OCTAL1  S  LEN(3) . I  =               WB
)@@G@@       :F(RETURN) @^@@@       I  =  BINOCT<I>   @G@@@       OCTAL  =  DIWC
)@@G@@FFER(I)  OCTAL  I              :S(OCTAL1)F(FRETURN)   @[@@@    *  @G@@@#WD
)@@G@@************************************************************************WE
)@@G@@@#@@@#4.2.2. OPERATORS. @G@@@    THE HANDLING OF OPERATORS HAS BEEN EXTEWF
)@@G@@NDED IN VERSION 3.  IT IS     @F@@@ NOW POSSIBLE TO PROVIDE YOUR OWN DEFWG
)@@G@@INITION OF UNARY OR BINARY    @F@@@ OPERATORS, OR TO RE-DEFINE (OR EXTENWH
)@@G@@D) THE OPERATORS PROVIDED BY  @C@@@ SNOBOL.  THE FOLLOWING SECTIONS DESCWI
)@@G@@RIBE THIS.  @@@@@ @ @@@#4.2.2.1. DEFINING OPERATORS.  @G@@@#   THE FUNCTWJ
)@@G@@ION OPSYN() HAS BEEN EXTENDED TO ACCEPT OPERATORS AS IF     @B@@@#THEY WWK
)@@G@@ERE FUNCTIONS.  THE GENERAL FORM IS:@@@@@#@^@@@#      OPSYN(F1,F2,N)    WL
)@@G@@@@@@@#@G@@@#WHERE F1 AND F2 ARE STRINGS CONTAINING EITHER IDENTIFIERS WHWM
)@@G@@ICH NAME    @G@@@#FUNCTIONS, OR OPERATORS.  THE EFFECT IS TO MAKE F1 A SWN
)@@G@@YNONYM OF F2.     @ @@@#N HAS THE FOLLOWING VALUES:   @@@@@#@G@@@#   N =WO
)@@G@@ 0 (OR NULL) MEANS THAT F1 AND F2 CAN ONLY CONTAIN IDENTIFIERS.   @G@@@#WP
)@@G@@         THIS MAKES OPSYN(F1,F2) WORK THE SAME AS IN PREVIOUS VERSIONS. WQ
)@@G@@@F@@@#   N = 1 SAYS THAT IF EITHER F1 OR F2 IS AN OPERATOR, IT WILL BE  WR
)@@G@@@B@@@#         INTERPRETED AS A UNARY OPERATOR. @G@@@#   N = 2 SAYS TO IWS
)@@G@@NTERPRET F1 AND F2 AS BINARY OPERATORS, IF POSSIBLE.  @@@@@#@#@@@#THUS AWT
)@@G@@ CALL OF    @@@@@#@^@@@#      OPSYN('F','*',1)  @@@@@#@B@@@#MAKES F(X) EWU
)@@G@@QUIVALENT TO *X.  SIMILARLY,  @@@@@#@^@@@#      OPSYN('$','F',1)  @@@@@#WV
)@@G@@@B@@@#MAKES $X RESULT IN A CALL OF F(X).  AND   @@@@@#@^@@@#      OPSYN(WW
)@@G@@'$','*',1)  @@@@@#@G@@@#WILL MAKE $X BEHAVE LIKE *X.  AS AN EXAMPLE USINWX
)@@G@@G BINARY OPERATORS,     @@@@@#@^@ @#      OPSYN('+','F',2)  @@@ @#@A@ @#WY
)@@G@@WILL CAUSE A + B TO CALL F(A,B).    @ @@@       OPSYN('SYSADD','+',2)   WZ
)@@G@@@ @@@       OPSYN('+','NEWADD',2)   @@@@@ @G@@@ WILL CAUSE SYSADD(A,B) TXA
)@@G@@O CALL THE SNOBOL4 ADD ROUTINE AND  A + B  TO   @#@@@ CALL NEWADD(A,B). XB
)@@G@@@G@@@#   ANY FUNCTION CAN BE USED AS AN ARGUMENT TO OPSYN.  HOWEVER, MANXC
)@@G@@Y OF  @G@@@#THE PRIMITIVE FUNCTIONS INSIST ON HAVING THE 'RIGHT' NUMBER XD
)@@G@@OF ARGU-    @E@@@#MENTS, AND THIS MAY CAUSE SOME PROBLEMS.  FOR EXAMPLE,XE
)@@G@@ WHILE@@@@@#@ @@@#      OPSYN('!','SIZE',2)     @@@@@#@G@@@#WILL BE ACCEXF
)@@G@@PTED, A ! B WILL THEN RESULT IN A CALL OF SIZE(A,B), AND    @F@@@#SIZE()XG
)@@G@@ PRODUCES AN ERROR IF IT ISN'T GIVEN EXACTLY ONE ARGUMENT.  @G@@@#   NOTXH
)@@G@@E THAT OPERATORS USED WITH OPSYN() MUST BE GIVEN EXACTLY.  THERE  @G@@@#XI
)@@G@@CAN BE NO EXTRANEOUS CHARACTERS, ESPECIALLY BLANKS.  THE BINARY OPERATORXJ
)@@G@@@E@@@#FOR CONCATENATION MUST BE REPRESENTED AS A SINGLE BLANK.    @@@@@#XK
)@@G@@@ @@@#4.2.2.2. AVAILABLE OPERATORS. @G@@@#   THE UNARY OPERATORS AND THEXL
)@@G@@IR INITIAL DEFINITIONS ON THE 1108 ARE:   @@@@@#@^@@@#   GRAPHIC   DEFINXM
)@@G@@ITION @A@@@#      \      NEGATION (FAILURE TEST)@B@@@#      ?      INTERXN

)@@G@@      *      EXPRESSION @^@@@#      /      UNDEFINED  @^@@@#      #     XQ
)@@G@@ UNDEFINED  @A@@@#      +      CONVERT TO NUMERIC     @A@@@#      -     XR
)@@G@@ NEGATIVE (ARITHMETIC)  @ @@@#      @      CURSOR POSITION  @^@@@#      XS
)@@G@@!      UNDEFINED  @^@@@#      &      KEYWORD    @@@@@#@ @@@#THE BINARY OXT
)@@G@@PERATORS ARE:     @@@@@#@G@@@#   GRAPHIC   DEFINITION                   XU
)@@G@@     PRECEDENCE ASSOCIATIVITY @F@@@#      \      UNDEFINED              XV
)@@G@@              12         RIGHT@F@@@#      ?      UNDEFINED              XW
)@@G@@              12         LEFT @F@@@#      $      IMMEDIATE ASSIGNMENT   XX
)@@G@@              11         LEFT @F@@@#      .      CONDITIONAL ASSIGNMENT XY
)@@G@@              11         LEFT @F@@@#      ",**   EXPONENTIATION         XZ
)@@G@@              10         RIGHT@F@@@#      %      UNDEFINED              YA

)@@G@@               1         LEFT @@@@@#@G@@@#NOTE THAT THE ONLY DIFFERENCESYK
