)@@G@@THERE IS AS YET NO WAY TO CHANGE THE PRECEDENCE OR    @A@@@#ASSOCIATIVITYN
)@@G@@Y OF A BINARY OPERATOR. @@@@@#@G@@@#************************************YO
)@@G@@************************************@^@@@#4.2.3. ERROR CONDITIONS.@F@@@#YP
)@@G@@   AN OPERATION IN SNOBOL4 CAN HAVE ANY OF FOUR TERMINATIONS:     @@@@@#YQ
)@@G@@@C@@@#      (1) SUCCESS, AND DELIVERY OF A VALUE.     @#@@@#      (2) FAYR
)@@G@@ILURE.@B@@@#      (3) ERROR, CONDITIONALLY FATAL.     @^@@@#      (4) ERYS
)@@G@@ROR, FATAL. @@@@@#@G@@@#THE THIRD TYPE, CONDITIONALLY FATAL ERRORS, IS NYT
)@@G@@EW TO VERSION 3.  IT    @G@@@#INCLUDES MANY ERRORS FORMERLY IN CLASS 4. YU
)@@G@@ CLASSES 3 AND 4 ARE LISTED   @[@@@#BELOW.@@@@@#@^@@@#4.2.3.1. ERROR CONYV
)@@G@@TROL. @F@@@#   THE HANDLING OF CONDITIONALLY FATAL ERRORS IS CONTROLLED YW
)@@G@@BY TWO@G@@@#NEW KEYWORDS, &ERRLIMIT AND &ERRTYPE.  IF &ERRLIMIT > 0, THEYX
)@@G@@SE ERRORS   @G@@@#SIMPLY CAUSE FAILURE OF THE OPERATION.  IF &ERRLIMIT =YY
)@@G@@ 0 (ITS DEFAULT   @G@@@#VALUE), SUCH ERRORS ARE TREATED AS FATAL ERRORS,YZ
)@@G@@ AND THE PROGRAM WILL   @G@@@#BE TERMINATED ABNORMALLY.  WHENEVER A CONDZA
)@@G@@ITIONALLY FATAL ERROR OCCURS, @G@@@#AND &ERRLIMIT > 0, &ERRLIMIT WILL BEZB
)@@G@@ DECREASED BY 1 AND &ERRTYPE WILL   @G@@@#BE SET TO AN INTEGER CODE FOR ZC
)@@G@@THE ERROR BEFORE THE FAILURE OCCURS.  IT  @G@@@#IS POSSIBLE TO TRACE &ERZD
)@@G@@RTYPE, AND SO A PROGRAM CAN DIAGNOSE ITS OWN    @C@ @#ERRORS IF DESIRED.ZE
)@@G@@  AS AN EXAMPLE, IF WE DO:    @@@ @#@^@ @#      &ERRLIMIT = 10    @@@ @#ZF
)@@G@@@#@@@ ERRORS IF DESIRED.@@@@@ @^@@@ AS AN EXAMPLE, IF WE DO:@^@@@       ZG
)@@G@@&ERRLIMIT  =  10  @G@@@#THEN THE NEXT 10 CONDITIONALLY FATAL ERRORS WILLZH
)@@G@@ CAUSE FAILURE OF THE   @F@@@#OPERATION THAT CAUSED THEM, AND THE 11TH EZI
)@@G@@RROR WILL BE FATAL.     @@@@@#@^@@@#4.2.3.2. ERROR MESSAGES.@@@@@#@A@@@#ZJ
)@@G@@THE CONDITIONALLY FATAL ERRORS ARE: @@@@@#@^@@@#1.  ILLEGAL DATA TYPE   ZK
)@@G@@@A@@@#2.  ERROR IN ARITHMETIC OPERATION   @B@@@#3.  ERRONEOUS ARRAY OR TZL
)@@G@@ABLE REFERENCE    @A@@@#4.  NULL STRING IN ILLEGAL CONTEXT  @A@@@#5.  UNZM
)@@G@@DEFINED FUNCTION OR OPERATION @^@@@#6.  ERRONEOUS PROTOTYPE @^@@@#7.  UNZN
)@@G@@KNOWN KEYWORD     @B@@@#8.  VARIABLE NOT PRESENT WHERE REQUIRED   @B@@@#ZO
)@@G@@9.  ENTRY POINT OF FUNCTION NOT LABEL     @B@@@#10. ILLEGAL ARGUMENT TO ZP
)@@G@@PRIMITIVE FUNCTION@#@@@#11. READING ERROR @^@@@#12. ILLEGAL I/O UNIT    ZQ
)@@G@@@B@@@#13. LIMIT ON DEFINED DATA TYPES EXCEEDED  @B@@@#14. NEGATIVE NUMBEZR
)@@G@@R IN ILLEGAL CONTEXT    @^@@@#15. STRING OVERFLOW     @A@@@#16. OVERFLOWZS
)@@G@@ DURING PATTERN MATCHING@@@@@#@B@@@#THE UNCONDITIONALLY FATAL ERRORS AREZT
)@@G@@:     @@@@@#@ @@@#17. ERROR IN SNOBOL4 SYSTEM   @ @@@#18. RETURN FROM LEZU
)@@G@@VEL ZERO    @A@@@#19. FAILURE DURING GOTO EVALUATION  @A@@@#20. INSUFFICZV
)@@G@@IENT STORAGE TO CONTINUE@#@@@#21. STACK OVERFLOW@B@@@#22. LIMIT ON STATEZW
)@@G@@MENT EXECUTION EXCEEDED @ @@@#23. OBJECT EXCEEDS SIZE LIMIT @A@@@#24. UNZX
)@@G@@DEFINED OR ERRONEOUS GOTO     @A@@@#25. INCORRECT NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS   ZY
)@@G@@@B@@@#26. LIMIT ON COMPILATION ERRORS EXCEEDED  @ @@@#27. ERRONEOUS END ZZ
)@@G@@STATEMENT   @D@@@#28. EXECUTION OF STATEMENT WITH COMPILATION ERROR     AA
)@@G@@@C@@@#29. TIME LIMIT EXCEEDED.     (NOTE: 1108 ONLY)  @@@@@#@C@@@#MORE EAB
)@@G@@RROR CODES MAY BE ADDED IN THE FUTURE.    @@@@@#@G@@@#   NOTE THAT TWO KAC
)@@G@@INDS OF FAILURE CAN OCCUR DURING A PATTERN MATCH.  IF @G@@@#ERROR 16 OCCAD
)@@G@@URS, THE PATTERN MATCH FAILS AS IF ABORT HAD BEEN MET.  ANY @G@@@#OTHER AE
)@@G@@CONDITIONALLY FATAL ERROR ACTS LIKE THE PATTERN FAIL, AND AN AL-  @^@@@#AF
)@@G@@TERNATIVE IS TRIED.     @G@@@#   ERROR 15 MEANS THAT A STRING WAS BUILT AG
)@@G@@WHOSE SIZE WAS GREATER THAN   @G@@@#&MAXLNGTH.  ERROR 23 WILL OCCUR IF TAH
)@@G@@HE SYSTEM CAN'T HANDLE AN OBJECT    @G@@@#THE SIZE OF THE ONE CREATED; TAI
)@@G@@HIS CAN OCCUR WITH STRINGS IF &MAXLNGTH IS@G@@@#SET TOO LARGE.  ON THE 1AJ
)@@G@@108, THE LARGEST POSSIBLE DATA OBJECT IS 2 ** 15@G@@@#DESCRIPTORS, WHICHAK
)@@G@@ FOR A STRING MEANS 12 * 2 ** 15 CHARACTERS (THERE    @A@@@#BEING 12 CHAAL
)@@G@@RACTERS PER DESCRIPTOR).@@@@@#@A@@@#4.2.3.3. EXEC8 ERROR TERMINATION.   AM
)@@G@@@G@@@#   PROGRAMS ARE OFTEN KILLED BY THE 1108 EXECUTIVE.  AN 'ERROR MESAN
)@@G@@SAGE' @G@@@#WILL APPEAR IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE LAST OUTPUT OF THE PROGRAMAO
)@@G@@, AND IT    @G@@@#WILL GENERALLY LOOK LIKE TOTAL GARBAGE.  IT DOES, HOWEAP
)@@G@@VER, CONTAIN A    @G@@@#RATHER CRYPTIC INDICATION OF WHY THE PROGRAM WASAQ
)@@G@@ KILLED, AND SOMETIMES  @G@@@#ANOTHER MESSAGE WILL BE PRINTED AMONG THE AR
)@@G@@MASS OF OTHER OUTPUT THAT     @G@@@#FOLLOWS, AND IT WILL EXPLAIN THE ERRAS
)@@G@@OR.  BUT THEN THERE MAY BE NO OTHER @F@@@#EXPLANATION, SO AN ATTEMPT WILAT
)@@G@@L BE MADE HERE TO EXPLAIN SOMEWHAT. @E@@@#THE FIRST LINE PRINTED BY THE AU
)@@G@@EXEC WILL BE OF THE FORM:     @@@@@#@^@@@#      LLLL DDDDDD DD    @@@@@#AV
)@@G@@@G@@@#WHERE 'L' IS A LETTER AND 'D' IS A DIGIT.  'DDDDDD' IS AN ADDRESS AW
)@@G@@WITHIN@G@@@#THE SNOBOL4 EXECUTIVE, AND IS OF NO VALUE TO THE SNOBOL4 PROAX
)@@G@@GRAMMER.    @F@@@#'LLLL' AND 'DD' TOGETHER CONSTITUTE A CODE FOR THE REAAY
)@@G@@SON FOR THE @G@@@#PROGRAM'S TERMINATION.  A LIST OF KNOWN VALUES FOR THEAZ
)@@G@@SE IS GIVEN HERE. @G@@@#IF ANYONE TURNS UP ANY MORE, IT WOULD BE APPRECIBA
)@@G@@ATED IF THEY COULD BE   @E@@@#DOCUMENTED AND REPORTED, SO THEY CAN BE ADBB
)@@G@@DED TO THE LIST.  @@@@@#@G@@@#   IGDM ------ 00  AN ERROR IN SNOBOL4--FIBC
)@@G@@ND OUT WHAT CAUSED IT AND     @D@@@#                   REPORT IT SO IT CBD
)@@G@@AN BE CORRECTED.  @G@@@^   I/O  ------ 22  YOU'VE TRIED TO WRITE PAST THBE
)@@G@@E END OF A FASTRAND     @F@@@^                   FILE.  MOST SYSTEMS WOUBF
)@@G@@LD RETURN AN END-OF-FILE@E@@@^                   INDICATION, BUT EXEC8 KBG
)@@G@@ILLS THE PROGRAM. @E@@@#   SYMB ------ 02  TWO CONSECUTIVE READ OPERATIOBH
)@@G@@NS FAILED.  @B@@@#   SYMB ------ 41  PAGE LIMIT EXCEEDED.   @B@@@#   SYMBI
)@@G@@B ------ 42  PUNCH LIMIT EXCEEDED.  @@@@@#@@@@@#@G@@@#******************BJ
)@@G@@******************************************************@^@@@#4.2.4. REAL BK
)@@G@@NUMBERS.    @G@@@#   THE HANDLING OF REAL NUMBERS HAS BEEN MADE GENERAL,BL
)@@G@@ SO THAT ALL THE  @G@@@#ARITHMETIC OPERATIONS AND FUNCTIONS WILL ACCEPT BM
)@@G@@INTEGERS, REALS, OR     @F@@@#STRINGS AS ARGUMENTS.  A STRING CAN BE EITBN
)@@G@@HER AN INTEGER STRING OR@G@@@#A REAL STRING, DEPENDING ON WHETHER IT CONBO
)@@G@@TAINS A '.' OR NOT.  IF ANY   @G@@@#ARGUMENT TO AN ARITHMETIC OPERATION BP
)@@G@@IS REAL, THE RESULT WILL BE REAL;   @B@@@#OTHERWISE THE RESULT WILL BE ABQ
)@@G@@N INTEGER.  @G@@@#   SIMILARLY, STRING OPERATIONS WILL ACCEPT BOTH INTEGBR
)@@G@@ERS AND REALS,    @G@@@#AND CONVERT THEM TO STRINGS.  THE EXACT RESULT FBS
)@@G@@OR REAL-TO-STRING CON-  @G@@@#VERSION ISN'T ALWAYS EASY TO PREDICT, AND BT
)@@G@@CAN BE EXPECTED TO BE DIF-    @G@@@#FERENT ON A DIFFERENT COMPUTER.  THEBU
)@@G@@RE WILL ALWAYS BE A DIGIT BEFORE    @B@@@#THE '.', BUT THERE MAY BE NONEBV
)@@G@@ AFTER IT.  @F@@@#   AS OF THIS WRITING, EXPONENTIATION CAN'T ACCEPT REABW
)@@G@@L ARGUMENTS.@G@@@#IF THIS IS TRIED, ERROR 5 (UNDEFINED FUNCTION) WILL OCBX
)@@G@@CUR.  HOPEFULLY   @G@@@#THIS WILL SOON BE REMEDIED.  WHEN IT IS, THIS PABY
)@@G@@RAGRAPH WILL BE REPLACED@^@@@#WITH ONE SAYING SO.     @G@@@#   CONVERT()BZ
)@@G@@ WILL CONVERT REALS TO INTEGERS, BY SIMPLY DISCARDING THE   @#@@@#FRACTICA
)@@G@@ONAL PART.  @@@@@#@G@@@#************************************************CB
)@@G@@************************@^@@@#4.2.5. NEW FUNCTIONS.   @G@@@#   IN ADDITICC
)@@G@@ON TO TABLE(), WHICH IS DESCRIBED IN SECTION 4.2.1, THREE   @ @@@#NEW FUCD
)@@G@@NCTIONS HAVE BEEN ADDED:@@@@@#@#@@@#4.2.5.1. DUMP(N). @G@ @#   THIS DOESCE
)@@G@@ A DUMP SIMILAR TO THE ONE PRODUCED AFTER TERMINATION IF    @G@ @#&DUMP CF
)@@G@@IS TURNED ON.  THE DUMP WILL ONLY BE PRINTED IN N > 0.  DUMP(N)   @B@ @#CG
)@@G@@RETURNS THE NULL STRING AS ITS VALUE.     @G@@@    THIS DOES A DUMP SIMICH
)@@G@@LAR TO THE ONE PRODUCED AFTER TERMINATION.  THE @G@@@ DUMP WILL ONLY BE CI
)@@G@@PRINTED IF N > 0.  DUMP(N) RETURNS THE NULL STRING.   @@@@@#@^@@@#4.2.5.CJ
)@@G@@2. DUPL(S,N).     @G@@@#   THIS CREATES A STRING THAT CONSISTS OF N COPICK
)@@G@@ES OF THE STRING S.     @#@@@#THUS, THE VALUE OF@@@@@#@#@@@#      DUPL('CL
)@@G@@+*',5)@@@@@#@F@@@#IS '+*+*+*+*+*'.  IF N = 0 OR S = '', THE NULL STRING CM
)@@G@@WILL RESULT.@G@@@#IF N < 0 OR S ISN'T A STRING (OR CAN'T BE CONVERTED TOCN
)@@G@@ ONE), DUPL(S,N)  @]@@@#WILL FAIL.  @@@@@#@^@@@#4.2.5.3. REMDR(M,N).    CO
)@@G@@@G@@@#   THIS RETURNS THE REMAINDER OF THE DIVISION M / N.  THE RESULT WCP
)@@G@@ILL   @^@@@#HAVE THE SAME SIGN AS M.@G@@@#   REMDR() HASN'T YET BEEN TESCQ
)@@G@@TED WITH REAL ARGUMENTS, SO ITS ACTION    @E@@@#IS THIS CASE ISN'T KNOWNCR
)@@G@@.  IT WORKS PROPERLY FOR INTEGERS.  @@@@@#@G@@@#************************CS
)@@G@@************************************************@A@@@#4.2.6. INPUT AND OCT
)@@G@@UTPUT CONTROL.    @F@@@#   THREE NEW KEYWORDS HAVE BEEN ADDED THAT CONTRCU
)@@G@@OL I/O OPERATIONS.@]@@@#THEY ARE:   @@@@@#@G@@@#&INPUT CONTROLS INPUT.  CV
)@@G@@IF &INPUT > 0, INPUT BEHAVES AS USUAL; IF &INPUT@G@@@#       = 0, ALL INCW
)@@G@@PUT ASSOCIATIONS ARE IGNORED AND NO INPUT IS POSSIBLE.@A@@@#       THE DCX
)@@G@@EFAULT FOR &INPUT IS 1. @G@@@#&OUTPUT IS SIMILAR TO &INPUT, BUT CONTROLSCY
)@@G@@ OUTPUT.  IF > 0, OUTPUT WILL @G@@@#       OCCUR AS USUAL; IF &OUTPUT = CZ
)@@G@@0, NO OUTPUT WILL OCCUR.  AN EXCEP- @G@@@#       TION TO THIS IS TRACINGDA
)@@G@@, WHICH IS CONTROLED SEPARATELY BY &TRACE.@C@@@#       THE DEFAULT VALUEDB
)@@G@@ FOR &OUTPUT IS ALSO 1. @G@@@#&TRIM, IF > 0, CAUSES THE FUNCTION TRIM() DC
)@@G@@TO BE APPLIED TO ALL INPUT.   @F@@@#       IF &TRIM = 0 (ITS DEFAULT VALDD
)@@G@@UE), THE ENTIRE RECORD WILL BE@B@@@#       DELIVERED, AS IN PREVIOUS VERDE
)@@G@@SIONS.@@@@@#@G@@@#   THE STATISTICS PRINTED AT THE END OF EXECUTION NOW DF
)@@G@@INCLUDE THE TOTAL @F@@@#NUMBER OF INPUT AND OUTPUT OPERATIONS PERFORMED DG
)@@G@@(OR ATTEMPTED).   @@@@@#@G@@@#   THE SECOND AND THIRD ARGUMENTS TO INPUTDH
)@@G@@() AND OUTPUT() CAN BE OMIT-  @F@@@#TED, AND THE STANDARD UNITS (5 AND 6DI
)@@G@@ ON THE 1108) WILL BE ASSUMED.@#@@@#IN PARTICULAR:    @B@@@#      INPUT(DJ
)@@G@@'X')   MEANS  INPUT('X',5,80) @D@@@#      OUTPUT('X')  MEANS  OUTPUT('X'DK
)@@G@@,6,'(1X,131A1)')  @@@@@#@G@@@#******************************************DL
)@@G@@******************************@A@@@#4.2.7. MISCELLANEOUS ADDITIONS.     DM
)@@G@@@@@@@#@#@@@#4.2.7.1. TRACE(). @G@@@#   THE SECOND ARGUMENT CAN NOW BE OMDN
)@@G@@ITTED, AND WILL BE 'VALUE'.  THUS:  @@@@@#@#@@@#      TRACE('X')  @@@@@#DO
)@@G@@@A@@@#IS EQUIVALENT TO TRACE('X','VALUE') @@@@@#@ @@@#4.2.7.2. &TRACE, &DP
)@@G@@FTRACE.     @G@@@#   THESE NOW ENABLE TRACING ONLY IF > 0.  FORMERLY A NDQ
)@@G@@EGATIVE VALUE     @#@@@#WOULD ALSO WORK.  @@@@@#@A@@@#4.2.7.3. STRING-TODR
)@@G@@-CODE CONVERSION. @G@@@#   A FINAL SEMICOLON IS NO LONGER NEEDED.  THIS DS
)@@G@@AFFECTS BOTH CODE(S)    @^@@@#AND CONVERT(S,'CODE')   @@@@@#@ @@@#4.2.7.DT
)@@G@@4. DEFINE() AND DATA(). @F@@@#   THESE HAVE HAD THEIR REQUIREMENTS FOR PDU
)@@G@@ROTOTYPE FORMAT SOMEWHAT@F@@@#LIBERALIZED, SO THAT EXTRANEOUS COMMAS AREDV
)@@G@@ IGNORED.  THEY FORMERLY@ @@@#PRODUCED ERRORS.  FOR EXAMPLE,@@@@@#@ @@@#DW
)@@G@@      DEFINE('F(X,,Y)W,Z,')   @@@@@#@#@@@#IS EQUIVALENT TO: @@@@@#@ @@@#DX
)@@G@@      DEFINE('F(X,Y)W,Z')     @@@@@#@ @@@#4.2.7.5. CONVERT(X,'STRING')  DY
)@@G@@@F@@@#   THIS NOW ALWAYS RETURNS A STRING.  IF X CAN'T BE CONVERTED TO ADZ
)@@G@@@F@@@#STRING, A STRING REPRESENTATION OF ITS TYPE WILL BE RETURNED.  FOREA
)@@G@@@]@@@#EXAMPLE,    @@@@@#@A@@@#      CONVERT(LEN(72),'STRING')     @@@@@#EB
)@@G@@@F@@@#WILL RETURN 'PATTERN'.  IF A IS AN ARRAY WITH PROTOTYPE '-3:3',   EC
)@@G@@@@@@@#@ @@@#      CONVERT(A,'STRING')     @@@@@#@ @@@#WILL RETURN ^ARRAYED
)@@G@@('-3:3')^.  @@@@@#@#@@@#4.2.7.6. -EJECT.  @G@@@#   THIS IS A NEW CONTROLEE
)@@G@@ CARD.  WHEN ENCOUNTERED BY THE COMPILER, A     @#@@@#PAGE EJECT OCCURS.EF
)@@G@@@@@@@#@#@@@#4.2.7.7. &CODE.   @G@@@#   A NEW UNPROTECTED KEYWORD, &CODE,EG
)@@G@@ IS PRESENT.  ITS PURPOSE IS TO     @G@@@#NOTIFY THE EXECUTIVE AND/OR LAEH
)@@G@@TER PROGRAMS OF THE TERMINATION STATUS    @F@@@#OF A PROGRAM.  IT IS USEEI
)@@G@@D TOGETHER WITH THE &ABEND KEYWORD IN THE @ @@@#FOLLOWING WAY ON THE 110EJ
)@@G@@8:    @@@@@#@G@@@#(1) IF &ABEND = 0, &CODE IS STORED INTO THE CONDITION EK
)@@G@@WORD (INTO T2,    @E@@@#   TO BE PRECISE), AND THE PROGRAM TERMINATES NOEL
)@@G@@RMALLY.     @G@@@#(2) IF &ABEND IS NON-ZERO, ITS ABSOLUTE VALUE IS STOREEM
)@@G@@D INTO THE CON-   @F@@@#   DITION WORD, AND &CODE IS IGNORED.  IF &ABENDEN
)@@G@@ > 0, AN ERR$ EXIT@E@^@#EQ() AND NE() WORK PROPERLY FOR 0 AND -0 IN VERSEO
)@@G@@ION 3.4.4.  @D@@@^   IS TAKEN; IF &ABEND < 0, AN ABORT$ EXIT IS TAKEN.  EP
)@@G@@@@@@@^@G@@@^SO FAR THERE IS NO WAY FOR A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM TO OBTAIN THE CEQ
)@@G@@ONDITION    @G@@@^WORD FOR THE RUN.  NOTE THAT THE USE OF &CODE AND &ABEER
)@@G@@ND IS VERY HIGHLY @#@@@^MACHINE-DEPENDENT.@@@@@^@G@@@^******************ES
)@@G@@******************************************************@ @@@^5. KNOWN BUGET
)@@G@@S IN SNOBOL4.     @@@@@^@F@@@^0 AND -0 ARE CONSIDERED TO BE UNEQUAL IN VEU
)@@G@@ERSION 3.4.3 BY EQ() AND@B@@@^NE(); THIS IS CORRECTED IN VERSION 3.4.4. EV
)@@G@@@@@@@#@G@@@#ARRAY() HAS A BUG IN VERSION 3.4.3 THAT CAUSES AN 'IGDM' INTEW
)@@G@@ERRUPT.     @B@@@#IT HAS BEEN CORRECTED IN VERSION 3.4.4.   @@@@@#@G@@@#EX
)@@G@@EVAL(S) HAS A PROBLEM IF S IS A STRING AND ISN'T SYNTACTICALLY CORRECT. EY
)@@G@@@F@@@#IT SHOULD FAIL IN SUCH CASES, BUT AT LEAST ONE VALUE OF S HAS BEENEZ
)@@G@@@G@@@#FOUND WHICH CAUSES AN ERROR 17 TERMINATION (ERROR IN SNOBOL4 SYSTEFA
)@@G@@M).   @F@@@#IT SEEMS TO WORK FOR ALMOST ALL STRINGS, BUT THERE ARE A FEWFB
)@@G@@ WHICH@G@@@#CAUSE EVAL() TO WIPE OUT THE PROGRAM.  THIS WILL PROBABLY TAFC
)@@G@@KE A WHILE  @#@@@#TO BE CORRECTED.  @@@@@#@I@@@#************************FD
)@@G@@********************************************************    @G@@@#******FE
)@@G@@******************************************************************@#@@@#FF
)@@G@@6. I/O FACILITIES.@G@@@#   THIS DESCRIBES THINGS ABOUT 1108 I/O NOT COVEFG
)@@G@@RED IN THE USERS MANUAL.@@@@@#@ @@@#6.1. LOGICAL UNIT NUMBERS.    @G@ @#FH
)@@G@@   THIS DESCRIBES THE CONCEPT OF 'LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER' FOR THOSE NOT    FI
)@@G@@@G@ @#FAMILIAR WITH IT, AND GIVES THE RELEVANT CONTROL CARDS FOR MANIPULFJ
)@@G@@ATING @[@ @#THEM. @G@ @#   SINCE SNOBOL USES THE FORTRAN LIBRARY I/O ROUFK
)@@G@@TINES, IT IDENTIFIES    @G@ @#ITS FILES BY 'LOGICAL UNIT NUMBERS', AS DOFL
)@@G@@ES FORTRAN.  A FILE NORMALLY  @D@ @#HAS A SYMBOLIC NAME DEFINED BY AN @AFM
)@@G@@SG CARD, AS IN:   @ @ @#      @ASG,MT  JOE.,T,1234    @F@ @#WHICH SAYS TFN
)@@G@@HAT THE NAME 'JOE' IS TO BE ASSIGNED TO THE TAPE 1234 @G@ @#(WITH MEDIUMFO
)@@G@@ DENSITY, NO WRITE RING).  SEE THE 1108 HANDBOOK FOR INFO   @G@ @#ON THEFP
)@@G@@ VARIOUS FORMS OF THE @ASG CARD.  TO USE JOE IN A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM @G@ @#FQ
)@@G@@(OR IN A FORTRAN PROGRAM, FOR THAT MATTER), A LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER MUST  FR
)@@G@@@G@ @#BE ASSOCIATED WITH THE NAME.  THIS IS DONE WITH A @USE CARD.  FOR FS
)@@G@@AN    @E@ @#EXAMPLE, TO ASSIGN LOGICAL UNIT 17 TO JOE, WE WOULD USE:    FT
)@@G@@@^@ @#      @USE  17,JOE.     @G@ @#WITHIN A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM, WE CAN NOWFU
)@@G@@ CREATE AN I/O STRING BY SOMETHING  @^@ @#LIKE THE FOLLOWING:     @F@@@ FV
)@@G@@   SNOBOL4 USES THE FORTRAN I/O ROUTINES, SO IT HANDLES I/O IN A  @F@@@ FW
)@@G@@MANNER SOMEWHAT SIMILAR TO FORTRAN.  THAT IS, I/O IS DONE ON FILES@F@@@ FX
)@@G@@THAT ARE IDENTIFIED BY INTEGERS CALLED 'LOGICAL UNIT NUMBERS'.  ON@G@@@ FY
)@@G@@THE 1108, FILES ARE GENERALLY IDENTIFIED BY NAMES THAT CONSISTS OF AT   FZ
)@@G@@@G@@@ MOST 12 CHARACTERS, INCLUDING LETTERS, DIGITS, OR THE SPECIAL CHARGA
)@@G@@ACTERS@G@@@ '-' AND '$'.  A FILE NAME CAN CONSIST ENTIRELY OF DIGITS, ANGB
)@@G@@D IF THE    @G@@@ NAME IS IN THE RANGE [0,30], A FORTRAN OR A SNOBOL4 PRGC
)@@G@@OGRAM CAN ACCESS  @G@@@ IT.  OTHER FILES ARE ACCESSED BY GIVING THEM ALTGD
)@@G@@ERNATE INTEGRAL NAMES.  @G@@@    A FILE IS CREATED ON THE 1108 EXTERNALLGE
)@@G@@Y TO A PROGRAM, BY USING AN   @D@@@ 'ASSIGN' CONTROL CARD, STARTING WITHGF
)@@G@@ '@ASG', SUCH AS: @^@@@       @ASG,T   15,F     @ @@@       @ASG,MT  JOEGG
)@@G@@,T,1234     @G@@@ THE FIRST OF THESE CAN BE USED DIRECTLY BY A SNOBOL PRGH
)@@G@@OGRAM, SINCE ITS  @G@@@ NAME IS AN INTEGER IN [0,30].  TO USE THE SECONDGI
)@@G@@ FILE, IT MUST BE GIVEN @G@@@ ANOTHER NAME WHICH IS NUMERIC.  THIS IS DOGJ
)@@G@@NE WITH A '@USE' CARD.  FOR   @G@@@ EXAMPLE, TO ASSIGN LOGICAL UNIT 17 TGK
)@@G@@O THE ABOVE FILE JOE, WE WOULD DO:  @^@@@       @USE   17,JOE.    @G@@@ GL
)@@G@@THIS FILE CAN NOW BE ACCESSED AS UNIT 17.  WITHIN A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM,    GM
)@@G@@@C@@@ WE CAN CREATE AN I/O STRING BY SOMETHING LIKE:  @ @@@#      INPUT(GN
)@@G@@'JOSEPH',17,N)    @C@@@#WHERE N IS THE MAXIMUM SIZE OF AN INPUT RECORD. GO
)@@G@@@D@@@#   IN SUMMARY, THREE THINGS ARE NEEDED FOR A FILE:    @B@ @#      GP
)@@G@@1) AN @ASG CARD, GIVING IT A NAME   @F@ @#      2) AN @USE CARD, GIVING GQ
)@@G@@A LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER TO THE NAME   @B@@@       1) AN @ASG CARD, GIVING GR
)@@G@@IT A NAME;  @G@@@       2) A @USE CARD, GIVING A LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER TO GS
)@@G@@THE FILE (NEEDED  @F@@@          ONLY IF THE NAME ON THE @ASG CARD IS NOGT
)@@G@@N-NUMERIC); AND   @G@@@#      3) A CALL OF INPUT() AND/OR OUTPUT() WITHIGU
)@@G@@N THE SNOBOL4 PROGRAM   @D@@@#         TO CREATE AN I/O STRING(S) FOR THGV
)@@G@@E UNIT.     @@@@@#@F@@@#   A LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER MUST BE WITHIN THE RANGGW
)@@G@@E [0,30].  SOME OF@G@@@#THESE NUMBERS ARE PRE-DEFINED BY THE FORTRAN I/OGX
)@@G@@ ROUTINES; THEY ARE:    @F@@@#      0  IS 'RE-READ'--IT CONTAINS THE LASGY
)@@G@@T RECORD INPUT FROM ANY @ @@@#         OTHER INPUT DEVICE.  @ @@@#      GZ
)@@G@@1  IS THE CARD PUNCH.   @ @@@#      5  IS THE CARD READER.  @ @@@#      HA
)@@G@@6  IS THE LINE PRINTER. @ @@@#     30  IS EQUIVALENT TO 0.  @@@@@#@G@@@#HB
)@@G@@FOR AN EXAMPLE, THE FOLLOWING PROGRAM READS FROM A TAPE FILE (IN SDF    HC
)@@G@@@A@@@#FORMAT) AND WRITES ANOTHER TAPE:    @@@@@#@^@@@#   @RUN  JOE,5362,HD
)@@G@@2971,3@B@@@#   @ASG,MT  TIN.,T,7392      . INPUT TAPE @B@@@#   @ASG,MT  HE
)@@G@@TOUT.,T,$4280    . OUTPUT TAPE@B@@@#   @USE     20,TIN.          . INPUTHF
)@@G@@ UNIT @B@@@#   @USE     21,TOUT.         . OUTPUT UNIT@^@@@#   @SNOBOL*LHG
)@@G@@IB.SNOBOL   @[@@@#   *  @B@@@#   *  SNOBOL4 TAPE PROCESSING PROGRAM.    HH
)@@G@@@[@@@#   *  @^@@@#      INPUT('TIN',20,80)@A@@@#      OUTPUT('TOUT',21,'HI
)@@G@@(80A1)')    @[@@@#   *  @E@@@#   R  CARD  =  TIN                        HJ
)@@G@@       :F(EOF)    @[@@@#   *  @A@@@#   *  CODE TO PROCESS CARD IMAGE.   HK
)@@G@@@[@@@#   *  @D@@@#      TOUT  =  CARD                              :(R) HL
)@@G@@@[@@@#   *  @F@@@#   *  THE FOLLOWING STATEMENTS SHOULD BE INCLUDED TO BHM
)@@G@@E SAFE:     @[@@@#   *  @A@@@#   EOF  ENDFILE(21);  REWIND(21)    @[@@@#HN
)@@G@@   *  @[@@@#   END@]@@@#   @FIN     @@@@@#@@@@@#@ @ @#6.2. FASTRAND DATAHO
)@@G@@ FILES.     @F@ @#   A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM CAN USE FASTRAND DATA FILES AS SEHP
)@@G@@RIAL FILES. @F@ @#CURRENTLY PROGRAM FILES AND ELEMENTS ARE INACCESSIBLE,HQ
)@@G@@ THOUGH THIS@G@ @#MAY CHANGE IN THE FUTURE.  THE ONLY PROBLEM THAT USERSHR
)@@G@@ ARE LIKELY TO    @F@ @#ENCOUNTER IS THAT THE RECORD SIZE IS LIMITED TO HS
)@@G@@84 CHARACTERS AT  @F@ @#THE MOST.  IF YOU ATTEMPT TO OUTPUT MORE THAN 84HT
)@@G@@ CHARACTERS, THE  @F@ @#OUTPUT WILL BE PRINTED IN SEVERAL 84-CHARACTER RHU
)@@G@@ECORDS, WITH BLANK@F@ @#FILL FOR THE LAST ONE.  ON INPUT, NO MORE THAN 8HV
)@@G@@4 CHARACTERS CAN  @G@ @#BE READ.  THUS IF YOU DO SOMETHING LIKE INPUT('FHW
)@@G@@F',20,100) AND UNIT     @A@ @#20 IS A FASTRAND FILE, THE STATEMENT@^@@@ HX
)@@G@@6.2. MASS-STORAGE FILES.@G@@@    THE 1108 HAS A MASS-STORAGE DEVICE CALLHY
)@@G@@ED A 'FASTRAND', A KIND OF    @G@@@ A LARGE DRUM WITH MOVABLE HEADS.  THHZ
)@@G@@ERE ARE TWO KINDS OF FILES THAT ARE @G@@@ IN COMMON USE ON THE FASTRAND,IA
)@@G@@ CALLED 'DATA' AND 'PROGRAM' FILES.  BOTH @G@@@ ARE STRICTLY SERIAL FILEIB
)@@G@@S, SINCE RECORDS ARE STORED IN A COMPACTED FORM.@F@@@ (RANDOM-ACCESS FILIC
)@@G@@ES ARE EXTREMELY DIFFICULT TO USE ON THE 1108.) @G@@@ SOME OF THE SOFTWAID
)@@G@@RE ON THE 1108 USES DATA FILES, AND SOME USES PROGRAM @G@@@ FILES; ALMOSIE
)@@G@@T NONE USES BOTH.  THE FORTRAN I/O ROUTINES CAN ONLY ACCESS @G@@@ (DIRECIF
)@@G@@TLY) DATA FILES, AND SO SNOBOL4 PROGRAMS ALSO HAVE THIS RESTRIC-  @F@@@ IG
)@@G@@TION, UNLESS THE SNOBOL I/O ROUTINES ARE SOMEDAY RE-WRITTEN.  BOTH@G@@@ IH
)@@G@@TYPES OF FILES ARE OF INTEREST TO A SNOBOL USER, HOWEVER, SINCE MOST    II
)@@G@@@G@@@ OF THE SYSTEM FILE-HANDLING PROCESSORS DEAL ONLY WITH PROGRAM FILEIJ
)@@G@@S.    @G@@@ (WHY THIS IS IS A MYSTERY TO MANY PEOPLE.)  SEPARATE SECTIONIK
)@@G@@S BELOW     @ @@@ DESCRIBE EACH TYPE OF FILE.   @@@@@ @ @@@ 6.2.1. FASTRIL
)@@G@@AND DATA FILES.   @F@@@    FASTRAND DATA FILES ARE HANDLED BY ROUTINES TIM
)@@G@@HAT MAKE THEM LOOK@G@@@ LIKE TAPES, AND THE USUAL TAPE OPERATIONS ARE MEIN
)@@G@@ANINGFUL ON THEM.  AS   @G@@@ USUAL ON THE 1108, THEY ARE WRITTEN IN A SIO
)@@G@@PECIAL FORMAT CALLED 'SDF'    @G@@@ ('STANDARD DATA FORMAT'--STANDARD ONIP
)@@G@@LY TO UNIVAC, OF COURSE), AND SO    @F@A@ BLOCKING FACTORS ARE NOT RELEVIQ
)@@G@@ANT.  ONE PROBLEM THAT USERS MAY RUN@F@A@ INTO IS THAT THE RECORD SIZE FIR
)@@G@@OR A FASTRAND FILE IS LIMITED TO 84 @G@A@ CHARACTERS AT THE MOST.  IF YOIS
)@@G@@U ATTEMPT TO OUTPUT MORE THAN THIS, THE   @G@A@ OUTPUT STRING WILL BE PRIT
)@@G@@INTED IN SEVERAL 84-CHARACTER RECORDS, WITH     @F@A@ BLANK FILL FOR THEIU
)@@G@@ LAST ONE.  ON INPUT, NO MORE THAN 84 CHARACTERS@F@A@ CAN BE READ.  THUSIV
)@@G@@ IF YOU DO SOMETHING LIKE INPUT('FF',20,100) AND@B@A@ UNIT 20 IS A FASTRIW
)@@G@@AND FILE, THE STATEMENT @ @A@#      OUTPUT  =  SIZE(FF)     @F@A@#WILL PIX
)@@G@@RINT '84'.  NO WARNING IS GIVEN IN SUCH CASES, SINCE THE I/O@G@A@#IS HANIY
)@@G@@DLED BY FORTRAN LIBRARY ROUTINES AND SNOBOL DOESN'T KNOW WHAT     @G@A@#IZ
)@@G@@IS HAPPENING.  IN ANY CASE, IF YOU KEEP YOUR RECORD SIZES TO NO MORE    JA
)@@G@@@D@A@#THAN 84 CHARACTERS, YOU SHOULDN'T HAVE ANY PROBLEMS.  @F@A@#   NOTJB
)@@G@@E THAT IF A LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER ISN'T ASSIGNED IT WILL BE A @D@A@#TEMPORJC
)@@G@@ARY FASTRAND FILE.  THIS IS OCCASIONALLY USEFUL.@A@@@ABLOCKING FACTORS AJD
)@@G@@RE NOT RELEVANT.  @G@@@A   THERE IS ONE THING YOU SHOULD TAKE SPECIAL NOJE
)@@G@@TE OF WHEN USING 1108   @F@@@AMASS STORAGE:  THE MAXIMUM SIZE FOR A RECOJF
)@@G@@RD IS 84 CHARACTERS.  IF@G@@@ABIGGER RECORDS ARE USED, THE RESULTS ARE LJG
)@@G@@IKELY TO BE QUITE UNRELIABLE  @G@@@AAND YOUR PROGRAM MAY DIE WITH SOME SJH
)@@G@@ORT OF A STRANGE DIAGNOSTIC.  IT    @G@@@ASEEMS THAT THE I/O ROUTINES HAJI
)@@G@@VEN'T BEEN VERY WELL DEBUGGED FOR RECORDS @G@@@ALARGER THAN A CARD-IMAGEJJ
)@@G@@.  SOMETIMES SUCH THINGS WILL WORK, BUT IT IS   @G@@@AMUCH SAFER TO JUSTJK
)@@G@@ STICK TO FILES WITH NO MORE THAN 84 CHARACTERS PER   @C@@@ARECORD.  SUCJL
)@@G@@H FILES SEEM TO WORK QUITE WELL.    @F@@@A   A USEFUL THING THE I/O ROUTJM
)@@G@@INES DO FOR YOU:  IF A LOGICAL UNIT @G@@@ANUMBER ISN'T DEFINED BY AN @ASJN
)@@G@@G CARD, IT WILL BE A TEMPORARY FASTRAND   @G@@@A(MASS-STORAGE) FILE, AS JO
)@@G@@IF A CARD LIKE THE FOLLOWING HAD BEEN USED:     @^@@@A      @ASG,T  <UNIJP
)@@G@@T>,F2 @@@@@A@F@@@#   THE FUNCTIONS REWIND(N) AND ENDFILE(N) WORK FOR FASJQ
)@@G@@TRAND FILES @F@@@#AS YOU WOULD EXPECT THEM TO.  THE PARAMETER IN BOTH CAJR
)@@G@@SES IS THE  @G@@@#LOGICAL UNIT NUMBER.  ALTHOUGH THEY ARE THEORETICALLY JS
)@@G@@NOT NEEDED AT     @G@@@#THE END OF A PROGRAM, IT APPEARS THAT THE 1108 EJT
)@@G@@XECUTIVE DOESN'T ALWAYS @F@@@#CLOSE FILES PROPERLY, AND EVEN IF IT DID, JU
)@@G@@OTHER OPERATING SYSTEMS @G@@@#MIGHT NOT.  THEREFORE, IT IS A GOOD IDEA TJV
)@@G@@O WRITE AN END-OF-FILE ON     @G@@@#ANY OUTPUT FILES (TAPE OR FASTRAND),JW
)@@G@@ AND REWIND ANY TAPES AT THE END    @G@@@#OF A PROGRAM.  THIS WILL MAKE JX
)@@G@@SURE THAT THE EXEC DOESN'T HAVE A CHANCE  @^@@@#TO LOUSE THINGS UP.     JY
)@@G@@@@@@@#@G@@@#   USERS SHOULD LOOK UP THE @DATA CONTROL CARD IN THE 1108 HJZ
)@@G@@ANDBOOK.  IT@G@@@#PROVIDES A HANDY WAY TO GET DATA FILES IN A FORM USABLKA
)@@G@@E BY A PROGRAM.   @G@@@#THE TAPE-HANDLING CONTROL CARDS (SUCH AS @ASG, @KB
)@@G@@COPY, @REWIND, @MOVE,   @G@@@#AND @FREE) ARE ALSO OF INTEREST TO ANYONE KC
)@@G@@WITH A LOT OF DATA.  SEE ALSO @G@@@#SECTION 6.3.1 FOR THE @ADD CONTROL CKD
)@@G@@ARD, ANOTHER THING THAT IS NICE TO  @E@@@#KNOW ABOUT BEFORE YOU START WOKE
)@@G@@RKING ON VOLUMES OF DATA.     @@@@@#@F@@@#   AS AN EXAMPLE OF THE USE OFKF
)@@G@@ FASTRAND DATA FILES TO COMMUNICATE @G@@@#BETWEEN SEVERAL PROGRAMS IN A KG
)@@G@@SINGLE RUN, IN THE FOLLOWING A FORTRAN    @F@@@#PROGRAM USES THE IOTPIN KH
)@@G@@FUNCTION (NOT AVAILABLE TO SNOBOL) TO READ@G@@@#A TAPE INTO A FASTRAND DKI
)@@G@@ATA FILE.  A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM THEN READS THIS    @G@@@#FILE AND WRITES ANKJ
)@@G@@OTHER FASTRAND FILE, WHICH IS THEN WRITTEN OUT TO     @F@@@#ANOTHER TAPEKK
)@@G@@ BY A FORTRAN PROGRAM USING IOTPOT (ALSO NOT AVAILABLE@]@@@#TO SNOBOL4).KL
)@@G@@@@@@@#@A@@@#   @RUN  SMITH,1111,2222,5,100/1000 @B@@@#   @ASG,MT  TIN.,TKM
)@@G@@,3333      . INPUT TAPE @B@@@#   @ASG,MT  TOUT.,T,$4444    . OUTPUT TAPEKN
)@@G@@@D@@@#   @ASG,T   FIN.,F2          . FIRST FASTRAND FILE    @D@@@#   @ASKO
)@@G@@G,T   FOUT.,F2         . SECOND FASTRAND FILE   @B@@@#   @USE     10,TINKP
)@@G@@.     . INPUT TAPE UNIT @C@@@#   @USE     11,FIN.     . INPUT FASTRAND UKQ
)@@G@@NIT   @C@@@#   @USE     12,FOUT.    . OUTPUT FASTRAND UNIT  @B@@@#   @USKR
)@@G@@E     13,TOUT.    . OUTPUT TAPE UNIT@E@@@#   @MSG,N   FORTRAN PROGRAM TOKS
)@@G@@ LOAD TAPE********************@^@@@#   @FOR,SI  .T-TO-F     @[@@@#   C  KT
)@@G@@@C@@@#   C  TAPE-TO-FASTRAND PROGRAM, USING IOTPIN.   @[@@@#   C  @[@@@#KU
)@@G@@   C  @ @@@#         DIMENSION  A(14)     @#@@@#         M  =  1  @[@@@#KV
)@@G@@   C  @A@A@#   1     IOTPIN(10,M,A,14,L,$10,$11)@B@@@A   1     CALL IOTPKW
)@@G@@IN(10,M,A,14,L,$10,$11) @ @@@#         WRITE(11,100)  A     @#@@@#      KX
)@@G@@   GO TO 1  @[@@@#   C  @^@@@#   100   FORMAT(14A6)   @[@@@#   C  @^@@@#KY
)@@G@@   11    M  =  1 - M    @#@@@#         GO TO 1  @[@@@#   C  @^@@@#   10 KZ
)@@G@@   ENDFILE 11     @]@@@#         END@B@@@#   @XQT                 . READLA
)@@G@@ THE TAPE   @E@@@#   @MSG,N   SNOBOL PROGRAM TO PROCESS FILE************LB
)@@G@@******@^@@@#   @SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL   @[@@@#   *  @^@@@#      INPUT('FIN',LC
)@@G@@11,84)@A@@@#      OUTPUT('FOUT',12,'(84A1)')    @[@@@#   *  @E@@@#   IN LD
)@@G@@CARD  =  FIN                               :F(EOF)    @[@@@#   *  @ @@@#LE
)@@G@@   *  CODE TO PROCESS CARD    @[@@@#   *  @D@@@#      FOUT  =  CARD     LF
)@@G@@                         :(IN)@[@@@#   *  @[@@@#   EOF@[@@@#   *  @A@@@#LG
)@@G@@   *  CODE FOR AFTER END OF FILE    @[@@@#   *  @#@@@#      ENDFILE(12) LH
)@@G@@@[@@@#   END@ @@@#      DATA DECK IF WANTED     @E@@@#   @MSG,N   FORTRALI
)@@G@@N PROGRAM TO WRITE TAPE*******************@^@@@#   @FOR,SI  .F-TO-T     LJ
)@@G@@@[@@@#   C  @A@@@#   C  FASTRAND-TO-TAPE, USING IOTPOT@[@@@#   C  @ @@@#LK
)@@G@@         DIMENSION  A(14)     @#@@@#         M  =  1  @[@@@#   C  @A@@@#LL
)@@G@@   1     READ(12,100,END=11)  A     @ @A@#         IOTPOT(13,M,A,14,$10)LM
)@@G@@@A@@@A         CALL IOTPOT(13,M,A,14,$10) @#@@@#         GO TO 1  @[@@@#LN
)@@G@@   C  @^@@@#   100   FORMAT(14A6)   @A@@@#   101   FORMAT(17HTAPE TOO SMLO
)@@G@@ALL.) @[@@@#   C  @#@@@#   10    PRINT 101@^@A@#   11    ENDFILE 13     LP
)@@G@@@^@@@A   11    CALL IOTPMK(13)@[@@@#   C  @]@@@#         END@D@@@#   @MSLQ
)@@G@@G,N   A MAP IS NEEDED, SINCE WE ALREADY HAVE AN @B@@@#   @MSG,N   ABSOLULR
)@@G@@TE ELEMENT IN TPF$.     @^@@@#   @MAP,I   ,.F-TO-T    @#@@@#   IN .F-TO-LS
)@@G@@T     @B@@@#   @XQT  .F-TO-T        . WRITE THE TAPE  @]@@@#   @FIN     LT
)@@G@@@G@@@#******************************************************************LU
)@@G@@******@^@ @#6.3. PROGRAM FILES.     @ @@@ 6.2.2. FASTRAND PROGRAM FILES.LV
)@@G@@@F@@@#   THERE IS ANOTHER TYPE OF FILE AVAILABLE ON THE 1108, CALLED A  LW
)@@G@@@F@@@#'PROGRAM FILE'.  SO FAR, IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO DO I/O DIRECTLY ON A LX
)@@G@@@F@@@#PROGRAM FILE FROM A SNOBOL4 PROGRAM (OR FROM A FORTRAN PROGRAM, ASLY
)@@G@@@G@@@#FAR AS I HAVE BEEN ABLE TO DETERMINE).  BUT THERE ARE A NUMBER OF LZ
)@@G@@SYSTEM@G@@@#PROCESSORS AROUND THAT CAN MANIPULATE PROGRAM FILES, AND IT MA
)@@G@@IS POSSIBLE @G@@@#TO USE THE @ADD CONTROL CARD TO COPY THINGS IN SUCH A MB
)@@G@@FILE INTO THE     @G@@@#INPUT STREAM.  THEY ARE QUITE USEFUL TO PEOPLE WMC
)@@G@@HO HAVE TO DEAL WITH    @G@@@#LARGE AMOUNTS OF DATA OR WHO WOULD LIKE TOMD
)@@G@@ STORE PROGRAMS OR FUNCTION   @G@@@#CODE ON TAPES FOR FUTURE REFERENCE. ME
)@@G@@ COMPLETE DOCUMENTATION WON'T BE    @G@@@#ATTEMPTED HERE; THE 1108 HANDBMF
)@@G@@OOK CONTAINS MUCH USEFUL INFORMATION,     @^@@@#AS DESCRIBED BELOW.     MG
)@@G@@@G@@@#   A PROGRAM FILE CONSISTS OF A SET OF 'ELEMENTS'.  THERE ARE MANYMH
)@@G@@ TYPES@F@@@#OF ELEMENTS, BUT SNOBOL4 USERS WILL ONLY NEED 'SYMBOLIC' ELEMI
)@@G@@MENTS.@B@@@#   AN ELEMENT'S NAME HAS THE GENERAL FORM:@@@@@#@#@@@#      MJ
)@@G@@Q*F.E/V(C)  @@@@@#@G@@@#OF WHICH Q, V, AND C ARE USUALLY OMITTED, LEAVINMK
)@@G@@G F.E AS THE USUAL FORM @G@@@#OF AN ELEMENT NAME.  THE VARIOUS PARTS OF ML
)@@G@@THE NAME HAVE THE FOLLOWING   @]@@@#MEANINGS:   @@@@@#@F@@@#   Q IS THE MM
)@@G@@'QUALIFIER', AND IS NORMALLY OMITTED, IN WHICH CASE A @D@@@#      SYSTEMMN
)@@G@@-GENERATED NAME IS USED AS A DEFAULT.     @F@@@#   F IS THE 'FILE NAME'.MO
)@@G@@  IF OMITTED, THE DEFAULT IS 'TPF$', THE  @G@@@#      'TEMPORARY RUN FILMP
)@@G@@E' THAT THE EXEC ASSIGNS TO EACH RUN.  IT MUST  @F@@@#      BE EITHER 'TMQ
)@@G@@PF$' OR A NAME CREATED BY AN @ASG CONTROL CARD. @D@@@#   E IS THE 'ELEMEMR
)@@G@@NT NAME', AND IS NEVER OMITTED.     @F@@@#   V IS THE 'VERSION', AND ISNMS
)@@G@@'T OFTEN USED.  IT IS ESSENTIALLY   @D@@@#      AN EXTENSION TO THE NAMEMT
)@@G@@, IF ONE IS NEEDED.     @G@@@#   C IS THE 'CYCLE NUMBER', AND IS AN INTEMU
)@@G@@GER.  WHENEVER AN ELEMENT     @G@@@#      IS UPDATED (SEE @ELT), THE SYSMV
)@@G@@TEM WILL GIVE THE NEW VERSION A     @G@@@#      CYCLE NUMBER ONE GREATERMW
)@@G@@ THAN THE PREVIOUS ONE.  EVERYTHING IN    @F@@@#      BOTH CYCLES WILL BMX
)@@G@@E SAVED, SO ANY CYCLE CAN BE REFERENCED BY@G@@@#      SPECIFYING THE CYCMY
)@@G@@LE NUMBER.  IF OMITTED, THE 'LATEST' CYCLE,     @G@@@#      WITH THE LARMZ
)@@G@@GEST CYCLE NUMBER, IS USED.  C IS NORMALLY OMITTED.   @@@@@#@F@@@#   EXCNA
)@@G@@EPT FOR C, ALL ARE 'IDENTIFIERS' THAT SATISFY THE SYSTEM'S  @G@@@#DEFININB
)@@G@@TION OF THE TERM (WHICH IS DIFFERENT FROM SNOBOL4'S).  THEY CAN   @G@@@#NC
)@@G@@CONTAIN LETTERS, DIGITS, MINUS SIGNS ('-'), AND DOLLAR SIGNS ('$'),     ND
)@@G@@@G@@@#AND THE FIRST CHARACTER MUST BE A LETTER OR A DIGIT.  THERE IS A LNE
)@@G@@IMIT  @^@@@#OF 12 CHARACTERS, ALSO. @G@@@#   THE '.' IS THE ONLY PUNCTUANF
)@@G@@TION IN AN ELEMENT NAME THAT MUST ALWAYS  @F@@@#BE INCLUDED; THE OTHERS NG
)@@G@@SHOULD BE OMITTED IF THEY AREN'T NEEDED TO@G@@@#SEPARATE PARTS OF THE NANH
)@@G@@ME.  SOME EXAMPLES OF NAMES OF ELEMENTS ARE:    @@@@@#@]@@@#      A.B   NI
)@@G@@@]@@@#      .C    @^@@@#      SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL @ @@@#      SNOBOL*LIB.SNJ
)@@G@@NOBOL-D     @^@@@#      PROG.INIT/V1-7    @#@@@#      SYS$*LIB$.X @]@@@#NK
)@@G@@      A.B(3)@@@@@#@F@@@#   THE FOLLOWING SUBSECTIONS DESCRIBE VARIOUS SYNL
)@@G@@STEM CONTROL CARDS@ @@@#THAT MANIPULATE PROGRAM FILES.@@@@@#@^@ @#6.3.1.NM
)@@G@@ @ADD <ELEMENT>.  @^@@@ 6.2.2.1. @ADD <ELEMENT> @G@@@#   THIS CAUSES THENN
)@@G@@ PROGRAM ELEMENT NAMED <ELEMENT> TO BE SUBSTITUTED FOR@F@@@#THE CARD.  TNO
)@@G@@HE ENTIRE ELEMENT WILL BE INSERTED INTO THE RUN STREAM@G@@@#AS IF IT HADNP
)@@G@@ BEEN PART OF THE DECK.  FOR EXAMPLE, IF A.B IS A SNOBOL4   @G@@@#PROGRANQ
)@@G@@M AND C.D IS A DATA DECK, THEN A.B CAN BE EXECUTED WITH C.D AS    @]@@@#NR
)@@G@@DATA BY :   @@@@@#@^@@@#      @SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL@#@@@#      @ADD  A.B   NS
)@@G@@@#@@@#      @ADD  C.D   @@@@@#@F@@@#THE TWO @ADD CARDS SIMPLY CAUSE THE NT
)@@G@@ELEMENTS TO BE COPIED INTO THE@G@@@#INPUT STREAM, AFTER WHICH THEY WILL NU
)@@G@@BE READ BY THE SNOBOL4 COMPILER     @]@@@#AND PROGRAM.@G@@@#   @ADD CARDNV
)@@G@@S CAN BE MIXED FREELY WITH ANY OTHER SORT OF CARDS.  CON-   @A@@@#SIDER NW
)@@G@@THE FOLLOWING FOR AN EXAMPLE: @@@@@#@^@@@#      @SNOBOL*LIB.SNOBOL@]@@@#NX
)@@G@@      -LIST @#@@@#         &DUMP = 1@^@@@#         TRACE('I')     @^@@@#NY
)@@G@@         TRACE('J')     @^@@@#         TRACE('AR1')   @^@@@#         TRANZ
)@@G@@CE('TX')    @^@@@#         &TRACE = 1000  @^@@@#      @ADD  A.MAINPROG  OA
)@@G@@@^@@@#      *  SUBROUTINES:   @#@@@#      @ADD  A.TRY @#@@@#      @ADD  OB
)@@G@@A.EXT @#@@@#      @ADD  A.INT1@#@ @#      END  START3 @]@@@       END   OC
)@@G@@@^@@@#      @ADD  A.DATA1     @^@@@#      @ADD  A.DATA3     @@@@@#@G@@@#OD
)@@G@@   ONE VERY USEFUL APPLICATION OF THE @ADD CARD IS TO COPY 'LIBRARY'    OE
)@@G@@@F@@@#FUNCTIONS INTO A PROGRAM.  BY USING CARDS DESCRIBED BELOW, IT IS  OF
)@@G@@@G@@@#POSSIBLE TO CREATE A 'LIBRARY' OF PROGRAM ELEMENTS ON A TAPE, AND OG
)@@G@@WHEN  @G@@@#ONE OF THEM IS NEEDED, THE LIBRARY CAN BE LOADED FROM THE TAOH
)@@G@@PE, AND     @E@@@#THE APPROPRIATE FUNCTION PUT INTO A PROGRAM BY AN @ADDOI
)@@G@@ CARD.@@@@@#@G@@@#   AN IMPORTANT FEATURE OF THE @ADD CARD IS THAT IT WIOJ
)@@G@@LL ALSO WORK FOR  @G@@@#DATA FILES.  THUS, IF A PROGRAM HAS WRITTEN A FAOK
)@@G@@STRAND DATA FILE NAMED  @#@@@#'D', THE CARD:    @@@@@#@#@@@#      @ADD  OL
)@@G@@D.    @@@@@#@G@@@#WOULD CAUSE ALL OF D TO BE COPIED INTO THE INPUT STREAOM
)@@G@@M.  SIMILARLY,    @F@@@#IF LOGICAL UNIT 27 IS ON FASTRAND AND HAS BEEN WON
)@@G@@RITTEN ON BY SOME @^@@@#PROGRAM, THEN THE CARD  @@@@@#@#@@@#      @ADD  OO
)@@G@@27.   @@@@@#@G@@@#WILL COPY THE FILE INTO THE INPUT STREAM.  FOR TWO EXAOP
)@@G@@MPLES OF THE USES @G@@@#OF THIS, IT IS VERY EASY TO COPY A DATA FILE INTOQ
)@@G@@O A PROGRAM ELEMENT, AND@F@@@#VICE-VERSA.  IF WE HAVE A DATA FILE NAMED OR
)@@G@@'A', AND WANT TO MAKE IT@G@@@#CONTAIN WHAT IS IN THE PROGRAM ELEMENT B.COS
)@@G@@, THE FOLLOWING WOULD WORK:   @@@@@#@#@ @#      @DATA,I A.  @#@ @#      OT
)@@G@@@ADD    B.C @]@ @#      @END  @E@@@       @USE  29,A.            . ASSIGOU
)@@G@@N UNIT NUMBER TO A.     @F@@@       @SNOBOL                . COPY IT WITOV
)@@G@@H A SNOBOL PROGRAM.     @A@@@          OUTPUT('OUT',29,'(80A1)')  @C@@@ OW
)@@G@@      L  OUT  =  INPUT                 :S(L)    @^@@@          ENDFILE(2OX
)@@G@@9)    @]@@@       END   @E@@@       @ADD   B.C             . ADD ELEMENTOY
)@@G@@ TO INPUT STREAM. @@@@@#@G@@@#A SNOBOL (OR FORTRAN) PROGRAM COULD THEN ROZ
)@@G@@EAD FILE A DIRECTLY.  SIM-    @F@@@#ILARLY, IF A IS A DATA FILE WHICH WEPA
)@@G@@ WANT TO COPY INTO THE PROGRAM@E@@@#FILE B, AND GIVE THE NAME B.C, THE FPB
)@@G@@OLLOWING WOULD WORK:    @@@@@#@#@@@#      @ELT,I  B.C @#@@@#      @ADD  PC
)@@G@@  A.  @@@@@#@B@ @#6.3.2. OTHER PROGRAM-FILE CONTROL CARDS.  @F@ @#   THEPD
)@@G@@ @ADD CARD WAS DESCRIBED IN DETAIL BECAUSE THE 1108 HANDBOOK@F@ @#DOESN'PE
)@@G@@T DESCRIBE IT (FOR SOME STRANGE REASON).  THE OTHER CONTROL @B@@@ 6.2.2.PF
)@@G@@2. OTHER PROGRAM-FILE CONTROL CARDS.@F@@@    THE @ADD CARD WAS DESCRIBEDPG
)@@G@@ IN DETAIL BECAUSE OF ITS IMPORTANCE@F@@@ TO JUST ABOUT ANY USE OF FILESPH
)@@G@@ ON THE 1108.  THE OTHER CONTROL    @F@@@#CARDS LISTED HERE ARE DESCRIBEPI
)@@G@@D IN THE HANDBOOK, SO THEY ARE JUST @G@@@#DESCRIBED BRIEFLY TO GIVE PEOPPJ
)@@G@@LE AN IDEA OF WHAT TO LOOK FOR IF THEY    @G@@@#NEED A PARTICULAR TASK DPK
)@@G@@ONE.  THE ONES MOST USEFUL TO SNOBOL4 USERS     @[@@@#ARE:  @@@@@#@F@@@#PL
)@@G@@   @ELT   IS THE MAIN ELEMENT-HANDLING CONTROL CARD.  IT HAS THREE@G@@@#PM
)@@G@@          MAIN USES:  IT CAN CREATE A NEW ELEMENT, READING ITS INITIAL  PN
)@@G@@@F@@@#          DATA FROM THE RUN STREAM.  IT CAN ALSO MAKE CHANGES TO  PO
)@@G@@@G@@@#          ELEMENTS THAT ALREADY EXIST.  AND IT CAN LIST AN ELEMENTPP
)@@G@@.     @@@@@#@G@@@#   @ASG   CREATES A FILE NAME AS ASSOCIATES IT WITH ANPQ
)@@G@@ I/O DEVICE.  THE @G@@@#          FILE CAN THEN BE FILLED WITH ELEMENTS PR
)@@G@@IF IT IS A FASTRAND     @E@@@#          FILE, OR READ INTO MASS STORAGE PS
)@@G@@IF IT IS A TAPE.  @@@@@#@A@@@#   @FREE  DESTROYS UNNEEDED FILES   @@@@@#PT
)@@G@@@D@@@#   @COPIN COPIES A PROGRAM FILE FROM TAPE TO FASTRAND.@@@@@#@E@@@#PU
)@@G@@   @COPOUT COPIES A PROGRAM FILE FROM FASTRAND TO TAPE.     @@@@@#@E@@@#PV
)@@G@@   @PRT,T PRINTS A LIST OF ALL ELEMENTS IN A PROGRAM FILE.  @@@@@#@B@@@#PW
)@@G@@   @DELETE MARKS AN ELEMENT AS 'DELETED'. @@@@@#@D@@@#   @PACK  REMOVES PX
)@@G@@ALL DELETED ELEMENTS FROM A FILE.   @@@@@#@I@@@#************************PY
